<TEXT>
bulgarias former communist ruler could 
soon face criminal charges his east german counterpart elderly 
and ill is under investigation for corruption and high treason 
and the former czech party chief is in limbo with charges against 
him still possible 
such is the fate of east europes leaders whose stalinist 
systems held 111 million people in the kremlins satellite 
countries in an iron grip for more than 40 years before being swept 
out by prodemocracy movements 
romanias nicolae ceausescu met a violent end he was executed 
dec 25 in part for ordering his security troops to fire on 
civilians who eventually overthrew his government 
only polands gen wojciech jaruzelski has managed to keep a 
government post 
the most dramatic changes came in east germany bulgaria 
czechoslovakia and romania in revolutions over a 10week period 
from october through december 
erich honecker the longtime communist leader of east germany 
was the first to go ousted by his own politburo on oct 18 as 
massive street demonstrations swept the country and thousands of 
citizens emigrated to the west 
prosecutors have been investigating honecker for corruption and 
abuse of power the nations top prosecutor hansjuergen joseph 
said monday the investigation had been expanded to include high 
treason and anticonstitutional associations 
honecker 77 underwent what was said to be successful surgery 
jan 10 to remove a malignant kidney tumor 
he had been placed under house arrest when the investigations 
first started but sources said a security cordon around honeckers 
opulent residential compound near east berlin was removed several 
weeks ago because no legal grounds were established to detain 
him 
at least 30 former top officials are under investigation in east 
germany and most are under arrest they include ousted trade union 
boss harry tisch and guenther mittag who oversaw the centrally 
planned economy 
bulgarias todor zhivkov was dumped by party comrades nov 10 
after 34 years in power for resisting reforms championed by soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev he too could face prosecution 
he has been accused of ruining the economy and leading bulgaria 
into international isolation largely because of his brutal 
suppression of the countrys 15 million ethnic turks 
we think the charges will be abuse of power fraud 
crimes against the consititution depriving the whole people of 
their rights said petar beron a member of a parliamentary 
investigatory commission 
the panel also is looking into the zhivkovs alleged diversion 
of bulgarian government funds into swiss bank accounts and misuse 
of state money to build more than 30 villas around the country 
zhivkov is being protected from the wrath of the people at 
his boyana residence near sofia beron said his trial date will be 
set after the investigation is completed probably in late january 
only one top communist functionary is known to be under arrest 
in czechoslovakia 
miroslav stepan the former prague party boss was charged with 
abuse of power allegedly for ordering the bloody crackdown on 
demonstrating students nov 17 that triggered the nations peaceful 
revolution 
national communist party chief milos jakes was ousted on nov 24 
and his fate is still unclear a parliamentary commission 
investigated the crackdown and apparently found that jakes was not 
involved 
however a separate communist party commission investigating 
abuse of political power ordered jakes stepan and vasil bilak the 
partys hardline ideologist to resign from the party 
gustav husak who came to power after the prague spring 
reform movement was crushed by the sovietled invasion in 1968 
resigned as head of state dec 10 
husak and 30 other senior officials were suspended from the 
party by a party congress earlier this month pending results of 
the party investigation 
ceausescu was toppled in a bloody revolution that began on dec 
15 
at least half a dozen members of the ceausescu clan including 
son nicu and daughter zoiaelena are under arrest and awaiting 
trial 
state television reported monday that another son valentin and 
ousted officials including former communist party secretary emil 
bobu will go on trial this week on charges of bringing economic 
ruin on romania and aiding genocide in the killing of thousands by 
during the december uprising 
in hungary where reforms came earlier janos kadar was removed 
as party leader in 1988 he died in july 
kadars reformist successor karoly grosz was overtaken by the 
pace of change and relieved last year by a new group of reformers 
they dissolved the communist party in october and established a new 
westernoriented socialist party 
in november hungarians voted overwhelmingly in a referendum for 
the party to make all its assets public 
the east bloc leader who seems to have best survived the 
revolutionary turbulence in eastern europe is polands jaruzelski 
the armed forces chief 
the polish national assembly elected him president july 19 and 
he has worked closely since then with the solidarityled government 
it was jaruzelski who decreed martial law in december 1981 to 
crush the independent labor union and it was jaruzelski who 
accepted the powersharing arrangement last summer when it became 
obvious that poland could not be governed without solidaritys 
participation 
</TEXT>
