<TEXT>
its been a year since the charismatic 
director of oregons prison system was stabbed to death outside his 
office authorities discount his familys claim that he was killed 
by corrupt elements within the prison system but concede they have 
no suspects 
the slaying of michael francke one of state governments rising 
stars last jan 17 distressed this capital city the fact that a 
massive investigation has yielded no suspects has kept interest in 
the case high 
it was about 1230 am and night watchman stephen rubino was 
told to be especially observant as he made his rounds of the dome 
building 
as he came to a dimly lit porch at the side of the building 
rubino spotted a large man sprawled on the porch he was surrounded 
by bloodstains and a panel of glass at the porch doorway was 
smashed 
the night watchman had discovered franckes body an autopsy 
would later show that francke died from a stab wound to the heart 
today the killing haunts those familiar with the case 
its been frustrating says marion county district attorney 
dale penn who has orchestrated one of most extensive criminal 
investigations in the states history 
despite interviews with thousands of people including several 
convicts and a reward fund exceeding 20000 the 20 or so 
fulltime investigators assigned to the case havent reported any 
big breaks 
penn said hes convinced the killer is a darkhaired man with a 
lightcolored coat who was seen running from the scene but that 
mans identity is unknown he said 
im not willing to predict when or if an arrest will be 
made penn said in an interview 
francke 42 was recruited from new mexico where he was 
director of prisons in may 1987 he was known for his dynamic 
speaking style and his trademark cowboy boots 
he apparently was attacked at about 7 pm as he was leaving 
work for the day and walking to his car parked outside the dome 
building headquarters of the corrections department 
despite his mortal wound francke managed to make it back to the 
building where he broke a panel of glass in a doorway before 
collapsing on the porch 
coworkers found franckes car with a door ajar in the parking 
lot but his body wasnt found until five hours later when rubino 
made his rounds under orders to be especially alert because francke 
couldnt be contacted 
though no arrests have been made the story has stayed in the 
news over the past year due in large part to the efforts of 
franckes family 
theyve publicly prodded investigators to pursue the possibility 
that francke was killed to prevent him from exposing highlevel 
corruption in the state corrections department 
penn and state officials say no one has produced any firm 
evidence to back that claim a recent investigation by a retired 
judge appointed by gov neil goldschmidt to look into the 
possibility turned up no link between franckes death and alleged 
corruption in the department 
in a report issued last month retired court of appeals judge 
john warden did find evidence of wrongdoing by about 15 corrections 
employees most of them guards but said there was no link between 
it and franckes death 
but franckes younger brother kevin francke said the family 
doesnt buy the revenge or robbery motives advanced by penn and 
others connected with the investigation 
kevin francke said he finds it especially unlikely that his 
brother who went to college on a football scholarship was killed 
when he interrupted someone trying to break into his car 
he pointed out franckes money wallet and rolex watch werent 
taken and that there was no sign of forced entry into the car 
he wasnt stupid enough to confront an individual with an 
8inch knife kevin francke said by telephone from port 
charlotte fla 
more likely he said francke was silenced before he had a 
chance to lower the boom on corrections officials guards and 
inmates who were involved in an alleged drug ring in the prisons 
he said michael francke had told him hed uncovered an organized 
criminal element in the department 
drugs and drug money i think thats the main thing kevin 
francke said i believe it involved corrections officials 
corrections employees and inmates 
for his part penn said his office has given lie detector tests 
to top corrections officials and found nothing to substantiate 
kevin franckes allegations 
i do not believe that corruption within the corrections 
department is a viable motive in this case the district attorney 
said 
it is unreasonable to believe that a whole group of 
corrections officials could pass polygraph exams and continue to 
conceal a conspiracy he said 
</TEXT>
