<TEXT>
the government of this citystate long a 
trading center for wildlife and wildlife products today announced 
that it will ban the import and export of ivory starting thursday 
in october the convention on international trade in endangered 
species adopted a ban on world ivory trading to save africas 
dwindling elephant population which has dropped from 15 million 
in the 1970s to an estimated 600000 now victims of poachers 
after their tusks 
the ban gives ivory traders until thursday to sell their stocks 
singapores ban does not apply to stocks of ivory already 
registered with the government the announcement said it did not 
disclose how much registered ivory was on hand 
imports of unregistered ivory have been prohibited in singapore 
since november 1986 when singapore became a party to the 
convention on international trade in endangered species 
in line with other moves by the convention the ministry of 
national development also announced a ban on the import and export 
of the moluccan cockatoo illisers macaw and the tucuman amazon 
parrot except for those already in stock as endangered 
also beginning thursday import and export permits will be 
required for the banded rattlesnake indian cobra and rhinoceros 
hornbill 
