<TEXT>
members of massachusetts armenian community 
stayed in touch with friends and relatives in azerbaijan on monday 
and urged moscow to prevent the bloody ethnic conflict from 
escalating into civil war 
there are thousands of armenians who live in azerbaijan and 
their lives are very insecure at this point said the rev dajad 
davidian of st james armenian church in suburban watertown what 
we want to see is some kind of public security take place 
dikran kaligian executive director of the armenian national 
committee of the eastern united states said the boston areas 
50000member armenian community is the second largest in the 
nation outside of los angeles 
in new york city armenianamericans demonstrated monday outside 
the soviet mission appealing for an end to the bloodshed 
its one of the saddest moments in contemporary history 
said archbishop megrob ashjian prelate of the armenian church of 
america and a protest leader in the eyes of the civilized world 
genocide is perpetrated 
about 100 protesters waved american and armenian flags chanted 
gorbachev stop the killing in reference to the soviet leader 
and sang a nationalistic anthem that translated as the enemy 
wants to kill us but we are here to stay 
ashjian said there are about 1 million armenianamericans 
150000 of them in the new york city area 
in los angeles garen yegparian executive director of the 
western office of the armenian national committee blamed the 
azerbaijanis most of whom are shiite moslems for the clashes with 
the armenians who mostly are christians 
what theyve started is not unexpected for us said 
yegparian its in line with their previous behavior 
kaligians watertownbased organization has been in constant 
contact with soviet armenians in azerbaijan everyone is involved 
because its a matter of life and death he said 
the violence broke out this weekend between predominantly moslem 
azerbaijanis and mostly christian armenians who are battling over 
nagornokarabakh a mainly armenian region of 160000 people 
controlled by azerbaijan since 1923 
official reports monday said hundreds of azerbaijanis and 
armenians fought with submachine guns helicopters and armored 
vehicles taken from military bases and that at least 37 had been 
killed 
kaligian said the death toll was probably a great deal higher 
those are obviously the initial figures he said the 
actual numbers are difficult to get because foreign newsmen are 
barred from the region 
manoog s young chairman of the board of the national 
association for armenian studies and research in suburban belmont 
predicted the hostilities could be quelled before a fullscale 
civil war broke out 
i dont think its a classic civil war situation he said 
i think before it will be allowed to get to that point im sure 
the soviet troops will intervene and put a lid on it 
somehow moscow has got to exert more influence they have to 
bring a stop to the bloodshed thats going on he said its 
come to the point that unless they get some control this will blow 
completely out of proportion 
kaligian said the reasons behind the fighting were not simple 
this situation is often being portrayed as a religious 
struggle or an ageold struggle kaligian said this is a 
political issue and an issue of survival 
davidian said the armenian community believes the azerbaijanis 
have more troops and more arms than the armenians making the 
battle difficult to win 
one of our big fears right now in the past week is now that 
theyve torn down the barriers we have a real fear that heavy 
military equipment is being taken into azerbaijan 
davidian said the civil strife in azerbaijan has taken a toll on 
the victims of armenias devastating december 1988 earthquake 
most of the supplies that come in from land come in through 
azerbaijan these supplies are effectively being blockaded he 
said 
 
