<TEXT>
throughout much of eastern europe there is a 
sense of exhilaration as the new decade dawns with the demise of 
authoritarian rule giving hope for a freer more prosperous future 
latin america was imbued with somewhat the same spirit 10 years 
ago when one by one discredited military dictatorships were 
surrendering power to elected civilians 
the democratic transformation of that region is now almost 
complete but in one sense latin americas evolution has brought 
more pain than progress over the past decade the average citizen 
is poorer now than in 1980 
east europeans may face a similar plight poles got a taste on 
new years day of how difficult the transition is from communism to 
a free market system the prices of gasoline and bus fares were 
doubled on jan 1 while the cost of heating oil and electricity 
rose fourfold it will be a while before poles live like parisians 
the experience in latin america must make some nostalgic for the 
era of corrupt dictators the 1980s are known in the region as the 
lost decade a time when up to half of its export earnings were 
consumed by foreign debt repayment when the average annual 
inflation reached 470 percent and when all the main indicators of 
economic performance production investment and consumption 
were below the levels of 10 years ago 
there were riots last year in two of the betteroff countries 
argentina and venezuela ironically the country with the best 
economic performance was chile where the generals are for the 
time being still in charge 
the decade of democracy has also been a decade of 
disillusion writes douglas payne of freedom house a 
prodemocracy research group in new york 
he blames powerful traditions of monopoly regulation and 
protectionism inherited from the colonial era and the huge 
moneyguzzling state corporations and corrupt nowork 
bureaucracies that were created during the 1960s and 70s 
indeed cuban president fidel castro thinks his country is doing 
quite well next to the latin american democracies the united states 
has assiduously promoted over the past decade many of his 
countrymen of course disagree 
castro has said cuba is the only country in latin america which 
has not closed factories schools or hospitals 
were the only country which is developing modestly but 
strategically castro said in an appearance before the national 
assembly that body approved a resolution pledging the island 
will first sink into the sea before we agree to pull down the 
banners of the revolution and socialism 
the resolution was approved on dec 27 just a few days after 
the people of romania ousted a system much like cubas in one of 
the most remarkable mass uprisings in modern history 
it was a regime which except for secret police hirelings 
seemed to have no defenders and the pattern was much the same last 
year elsewhere in eastern europe 
the question now is whether that region will suffer the same 
economic fate as the new democracies in latin america 
robert d hormats a former top state department economic 
affairs expert warns the transition and the new leadership in 
eastern europe could be jeopardized if living standards do not 
quickly improve 
economic transformation will take years hormats says in 
the near term cutting subsidies for food and rent closing 
obsolete plants and laying off redundant workers could lower living 
standards 
he says the west would make one of the great mistakes in 
history if it refuses to spend the several billions needed to help 
countries through this hard period 
it is more difficult hormats says to create successful 
market economies than tear down failing socialist economies it 
will be harder still if eastern europeans do not work together and 
if the west fails to help them do so 
</TEXT>
