<TEXT>
members of congress get much more attention 
from television network news when they run for president than for 
their nutsandbolts work in washington says a new study 
democrat richard gephardt barely rated a mention on the evening 
news for his congressional work on the federal tax code but a bid 
for the presidency in 1988 propelled him into prime time 
the same was true for albert gore jr lloyd bentsen paul simon 
and dan quayle who found that mention on cbs nbc and abc was the 
result of their political aspirations rather than their jobs in 
congress 
as an everyday member of congress they might not ever be 
mentioned said joe s foote a former congressional staffer and 
chairman of the radiotelevision department at southern illinois 
university in carbondale 
in fact 44 percent of the house members were never mentioned on 
the nightly news programs during 198788 footes study said 
as the 1980s passed by congressional backbenchers found it 
was harder and harder to break into the national spotlight as 
defined by abc cbs and nbc foote said 
the result is that some of the newer and younger members of 
congress have fewer and fewer opportunities to influence public 
opinion he said we rarely hear their ideas 
foote who has conducted the annual analysis of lawmakers tv 
visibility for nearly a decade said the study released this week 
shows that gephardt who made an unsuccessful bid for the 
democratic presidential nomination in 1988 was mentioned just 25 
times on the nightly news in 198586 during the 99th congress 
during the 100th congress shortly after gephardt announced his 
candidacy in february 1987 he totaled 253 mentions that included 
use of his name in a report a film clip or an interview 
foote based the study on the television news index and abstracts 
at the vanderbilt university news archive in nashville tenn 
which tracked mentions on the evening news programs of the three 
networks cable news network was not included 
for other lawmakers the jump from obscurity to oftenmentioned 
was a major leap after they sought the presidency or vice 
presidency sen joseph biden ddel a 1988 presidential 
candidate was mentioned 35 times in 198586 104 in 198788 
sen albert gore jr of tennessee another 1988 democratic 
hopeful rose from 27 mentions in 198586 to 209 in 198788 sen 
paul simon dill rated 15 mentions in 198586 but 200 in 
198788 
dan quayle the republican senator from indiana received six 
mentions in 198586 but skyrocketed to 172 in 198788 which 
included his election as vice president 
heading the list of mentions among the lawmakers who sought 
higher office was senate minority leader bob dole rkan with 276 
in 198586 and 486 in 198788 by virtue of those totals dole also 
led all 100 senators in tv exposure in 198788 
