<TEXT>
cutbacks in sales of hardwood timber products 
by some southeast asian countries are putting pressure on the 
united states to export more logs and rough lumber according to an 
agriculture department report 
indonesia recently announced large increases in export taxes 
that make the export of hardwood logs and lumber nearly 
prohibitive the report said 
the action puts indonesia among a growing number of asian 
countries that are curbing exports of logs and rough lumber in 
favor of sending furniture and other valueadded products made 
from wood abroad 
malaysia and the philippines have previously taken action to 
curb such exports while taiwan and thailand have officially banned 
commercial logging the report said these actions are 
increasing the pressure on the us industry to fill this growing 
gap in international supply 
the report by the departments foreign agricultural service said 
the value of us exports of solid wood products were up 15 percent 
from a year earlier in the first nine months of 1989 while imports 
were up only 7 percent 
overall exports were valued at nearly 459 billion in the 
first three quarters of last year japan accounted for 22 
billion or 48 percent of the us wood exports mostly as softwood 
logs 
canada was the secondlargest market during the 
januaryseptember period with 5015 million or 11 percent of the 
total south korea was another big overseas buyer at 2676 million 
analyst margie bauer of the usda agency said the furniture 
industry is undergoing major changes and there are opportunities 
for us exporters 
currently taiwan and to a smaller degree korea are the 
major furniture exporters in asia she said in the report the 
export furniture industries in taiwan and korea are facing severe 
problems such as workers demanding higher wages a shortage of 
labor and high production costs 
bauer added thus the industries are relocating to southeast 
asia primarily thailand malaysia singapore and indonesia 
manufacturers in taiwan and korea rely heavily on hardwood logs 
from southeast asia and hardwood products from north america 
the recent restrictions on exports by some of the southeast 
asian countries however have reduced the supply of relatively 
inexpensive hardwood logs she said as a result us hardwood 
logs lumber veneers and panel products have an enormous 
potential market in the new furniture producing countries 
while the industry in these countries is young and 
inexperienced there is little doubt that it will grow 
tremendously bauer said now is the time for the us industry 
to work together in educating these countries on the advantages of 
using us hardwoods in the manufacturing of furniture 
</TEXT>
