<TEXT>
thirteen other industrial nations spend 
relatively more on elementary and secondary education than the 
united states says a report that challenges president bushs 
assertion that results not resources are the problem 
the united states leads only ireland and australia among 
industrial nations the laborbacked economic policy institute said 
monday in a briefing paper shortchanging education 
if the us were to increase spending for primary and 
secondary school up to the average level found in the other 15 
countries we would need to raise spending by over 20 billion 
annually said the report 
m edith rasell author of the report said the results were 
based on data published by the united nations educational 
scientific and cultural organization and by the federal government 
it focused on elementary and secondary education spending for 1985 
comparing expenditures as a percentage of national income 
the education department disputed the studys findings deputy 
undersecretary charles kolb in charge of the agencys budget said 
the institute used seriously flawed methodology to reach dubious 
conclusions 
kolb said the institute has mixed apples oranges and 
moonbeams to produce an indigestible concoction he said the 
united states ranks among the top five countries by the 
departments calculations 
its fun to play with numbers but it can be a dangerous 
delusion if used as a basis for public policy he said if 
nothing else this report points out the need for better math 
education 
the institutes statistics show the united states spent 41 
percent of its national income on k12 education in 1985 while the 
average abroad was 46 percent sweden spent 7 percent followed by 
austria at 59 percent switzerland at 58 percent norway at 53 
percent belgium at 49 percent and denmark and japan at 48 
percent 
canada spent 47 percent west germany and france 46 percent 
the netherlands and united kingdom 45 percent and italy 42 
percent 
behind the united states in spending australia spent 39 
percent and ireland spent 38 percent 
ms rasell said this is the first time that economists have 
examined the factual underpinnings of the bush administrations 
claims about education spending 
the report pointed to president bushs statement at last falls 
education summit that the us lavishes unsurpassed resources on 
schooling and our focus must no longer be on resources it 
must be on results 
according to the report we recognize that money does not 
guarantee excellence and we suspect that other changes in 
curriculum in the status of teachers and in expectations about 
students to name just a few will also be fundamental to any 
improvement in education quality and student achievement 
but to begin a process of education reform by denying the need 
to increase spending especially when us schools are underfunded 
compared to those in other industrialized countries places a 
severely limiting constraint on any plans for educational 
improvement 
to show problems with comparing relative expenditures kolb said 
that in 1986 mississippi spent per pupil 39 percent of its state 
domestic product while minnesota spent 37 percent however in 
dollars mississippi spent only 2350 per pupil compared with 
minnesotas 4180 
the report acknowledged that the us spends comparatively 
more than other countries on higher education ms rasell said 
that when expenditures on all levels of education preprimary 
primary secondary and postsecondary are calculated the united 
states is in a threeway tie for second place among the countries 
studied 
but when spending on higher education is removed from 
comparative data the report said the relative position of us 
spending falls from a threeway tie for second highest in spending 
to close to the bottom of the group of 16 industrial nations 
