<TEXT>
groundwater pumping by the antelope 
valleys growing population is cracking and sinking the dry lakebed 
runways famed as landing strips for space shuttles and test pilots 
during a california water commission hearing here last week air 
force officials said the floor of rogers dry lake has subsided 3 
feet in some places and is broken by fissures up to 3 feet wide 2 
feet deep and hundreds of feet long 
the air force has been able to keep using the clay runways only 
by filling in the cracks 
were seeing severe cracks throughout the whole lakebed 
said col peter walsh civil engineer for the mojave desert 
military base 
many space shuttles have landed on dry lakebed runways although 
columbia was scheduled to touch down on a concrete landing strip on 
friday 
the us geological survey is conducting a 6 million fiveyear 
study of the problem and other wateruse issues for the air force 
its very obvious groundwater pumpage is having an impact on 
the subsidence at edwards air force base said john klein 
district chief of the surveys water resources division 
klein said the sinking and related drinkingwater shortages at 
edwards will continue unless major steps are taken to limit 
further withdrawals of ground water 
water use has climbed during the past decade as the population 
of the antelope valley which includes lancaster and palmdale 
doubled to almost 200000 air force officials are urging local 
water agencies to use less ground water and use more water brought 
from the north via the california aqueduct 
the water table at edwards dropped from about 10 feet below the 
surface in 1948 to a recent level of 100 feet underground klein 
said adding it is difficult to determine how much of the drop is 
caused by population growth 
edwards is 300000 acres the secondlargest air force base in 
the continental united states it is home to the famed flight test 
