<TEXT>
space shuttle columbias five crew 
members labored quietly today on their experiments growing protein 
crystals in zero gravity melting and resolidifying a metal and 
photographing the earth 
all systems aboard columbia are clean mission control 
reported as the astronauts worked through the seventh full day of 
their marathon 10day mission 
there was little radio traffic between ground and space to 
allow the crew to stay on the timeline and get all their various 
chores accomplished without a lot of interference from the folks 
here the control center said 
we just let them go at it and theyve been doing very well 
television from the shuttle showed the astronauts busily 
pursuing the several experiments 
there were no further problems with a navigation system that 
sounded an alarm and wakened the crew sunday night and commander 
dan brandenstein stopped a dehumidifier leak that had been a bother 
almost from the beginning of the flight 
engineers did not have an explanation for the five sensor 
signals that triggered the alarm but some theorized they may have 
been associated with electronics that feed a speedmeasuring 
accelerometer and not with the navigation unit itself 
brandenstein plugged the leak by stuffing a towel in a plastic 
bag and wrapping it around the pipe that was its source 
the astronauts were so busy with their experiments monday that 
they went to bed more than two hours late so mission control let 
them sleep an extra half hour today 
but it told them in the package of messages and instructions 
faxed up this morning your request for overtime has been 
disapproved 
one of the crews first chores was to dump excess water 
overboard through a valve a tv picture showed the expelled water 
turning to ice crystals as it hit the cold atmosphere of space as 
columbia passed into daylight the sun brilliantly illuminated the 
crystal shower 
quite a show isnt it brandenstein remarked 
you bet replied mission control communicator tammy jernigan 
mission specialists bonnie dunbar marsha ivins and david low 
were busy monitoring an experiment in which the metal indium was 
being melted and resolidified to determine if spaceprocessed 
materials can have industrial applications 
they also were growing protein crystals in a continuing series 
of shuttle experiments that could lead to the weightless processing 
of new purer drugs to be used to fight cancer aids high blood 
pressure arthritis and other diseases 
medical experiments were aimed at learning how well the human 
body adapts to weightlessness 
brandenstein and pilot jim wetherbee when not minding the ship 
were busy photographing earth features for a documentary film on 
how man and nature are damaging the planet 
among the targets were large fires in kenya and madagascar and 
deforestation in brazil and haiti 
the astronauts accomplished their main goals during the first 
four days of the mission they deployed a navy communications 
satellite and retrieved an 11ton science laboratory that they will 
bring back to earth so scientists can learn how scores of different 
materials and systems survived six years in orbit 
columbia is to land in the darkness at 259 am pst on friday 
at edwards air force base calif 
