<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let a 
machinists union strike against eastern airlines spread to commuter 
railroads 
the court without comment left intact rulings barring sympathy 
strikes against railroads in new york city philadelphia and their 
suburbs 
the machinists who walked off the job last march 4 after 
refusing to give more than 150 million in concessions sought by 
eastern remain on strike pilots and flight attendants supported 
the strike for eight months before ending their walkout in 
november 
the machinists and unions sympathetic to the eastern strike 
sought to extend its impact by setting up picket lines at 
facilities run by the southeastern pennsylvania transportation 
authority septa in the philadelphia area and by amtrak the long 
island railroad metronorth commuter railroad and nj transit rail 
in the new york city metropolitan area 
the new york cityarea railroads carry some 350000 commuters 
daily between new york city and its suburbs the septa trains 
transport more than 90000 commuters each day 
federal judges barred the secondary strikes and the restraining 
orders were upheld by the new yorkbased 2nd us circuit court of 
appeals and the philadelphiabased 3rd us circuit court of 
appeals 
the appeals courts said collective bargaining agreements between 
the railroads and their unions may be interpreted to prohibit such 
sympathy strikes at least until the labor dispute is submitted to 
arbitration 
underlying the issue is a clash between two federal laws the 
railway labor act and the norrisla guardia act 
the norrisla guardia act limits the power of federal courts to 
enjoin strikes while the railway labor act sets up procedures such 
as arbitration designed to forestall strikes against railroads 
the justices in 1987 ruled that courts generally may not bar 
railroad workers from extending a labor dispute to other railroads 
not directly involved in the dispute 
but the 2nd circuit court said the 1987 ruling applies only in 
cases in which other procedures to end a railway strike are 
exhausted 
the appeals court said the opposite was true in the eastern case 
because there had been no attempt through arbitration to end the 
secondary strikes against the railroads 
since there was a risk of immediate and irreparable injury to 
the railroads and the public the 2nd circuit court said the 
judge acted within his authority in halting the sympathy strikes 
the 3rd circuit court said septa workers do not have the right 
to violate nostrike provisions in their own collective bargaining 
agreements by honoring picket lines set up by eastern employees at 
septa facilities 
lawyers for the machinists union said the power of unions to 
fight for fair treatment is weakened by a ban on sympathy strikes 
they also said the 2nd and 3rd circuit court rulings conflict with 
decisions by other federal appeals courts 
there have been reports that the machinists want to use sympathy 
strikes against the railroads to prompt president bush or congress 
to take action in their walkout against the airline 
the cases are international association of machinists vs long 
island railroad 89427 and 89674 and brotherhood of railroad 
signalmen vs septa 89756 
