<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide what 
authority police have to stop and question someone on the basis of 
an anonymous tip that the person is involved in a crime 
the justices said they will review an alabama court ruling that 
limited such police tactics 
a state appeals court threw out vanessa whites 1987 conviction 
for possession of marijuana and cocaine ruling that montgomery 
police had seized the drugs after unlawfully stopping her car 
the appeals court said an anonymous tip police received about 
ms white was not enough to justify an investigatory stop by police 
and they therefore had violated her constitutional rights 
the constitutions fourth amendment bans unreasonable police 
seizures and searches 
ms whites twoyear probationary sentence was thrown out along 
with her conviction 
the nations highest court previously has ruled that police can 
make arrests only when they have probable cause to believe 
someone is involved in a crime 
but the court has allowed police to make brief investigatory 
stops to stop question and even frisk someone if they have a 
reasonable suspicion a more lenient standard than probable 
cause 
federal appeals courts and state courts have been divided in 
recent years when ruling whether an anonymous tip to police can 
give rise to such a reasonable suspicion 
in ms whites case the alabama appeals court based its 
decision on an individualized evaluation of the particular tip in 
light of the totality of the circumstances 
on april 22 1987 police cpl bh davis received an anonymous 
telephone call telling him that ms white would be leaving a 
certain apartment at a particular time in a brown station wagon to 
go to a motel the caller said ms white would have with her about 
an ounce of cocaine in a brown attache case 
police went to the apartment and kept it under surveillance 
they saw ms white leave in a brown station wagon and drive to a 
motel they then approached ms white and told her about the call 
they had received 
an officer asked for permission to search the station wagon and 
ms white said he could a brown attache case was found inside and 
after ms white told officers the combination to its lock 
marijuana was found inside it 
after ms white was arrested police found three milligrams of 
cocaine inside her purse 
in throwing out ms whites conviction the state appeals court 
said because she was illegally detained when she gave her 
consent to the search the marijuana from the briefcase and the 
cocaine from her purse are fruits of an unconstitutional 
detention 
such evidence should have been barred from her prosecution the 
appeals court said 
it added here the stop cannot be supported by specific and 
articulable reliable facts raising a reasonable suspicion that ms 
white was engaged in wrongdoing 
after the alabama supreme court refused to review the case 
state attorney general don siegelman filed the appeal acted on 
today 
the justices in 1980 and 1981 turned down requests to decide 
whether an anonymous tip can justify an investigatory stop each 
time several justices voted to resolve the issue 
the case is alabama vs white 89789 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

