<TEXT>
trans world airlines flight attendants who 
accused twa owner carl icahn of sex bias in seeking wage cuts and 
other concessions that triggered a strike lost a supreme court 
appeal today 
the court without comment refused to revive a lawsuit against 
the airline the flight attendants sought back pay and other 
benefits 
the independent federation of flight attendants called a strike 
against twa on march 7 1986 two months later the union offered 
to return to work and accept twas demands 
about 200 strikers were rehired immediately but more than three 
years passed before the last of the 5000 striking attendants were 
offered jobs with twa 
the strike was called when icahn insisted on wage and other 
concessions for attendants 85 percent of them women that were 
greater than cuts he sought to impose against the airlines pilots 
machinists and other workers 
during the negotiations with the attendants union icahn said it 
would be easy for him to find young untrained women to be 
stewardesses for less than he was paying the attendants 
when union negotiators said janitors who belonged to the 
machinists union were offered a better deal than the attendants 
icahn remarked 
a janitor is a breadwinner who probably has got a family at 
home to support while you girls are second incomes and you dont 
need the money 
the union said the statement demonstrated bias against women and 
violated fair bargaining procedures mandated by the federal railway 
labor act which governs labor negotiations for airlines and 
railroads 
the strike against twa should be viewed by the courts as one 
based on unfair labor practices and not only on demands for more 
money the unions lawyers said 
unlike workers who walk off the job over pay and benefits 
strikers who prove unfair labor practices by an employer are 
entitled to their old jobs when they unconditionally return to work 
us district judge howard f sachs in missouri rejected the 
unions claims that icahn was guilty of sexual stereotyping 
icahns breadwinner remarks were foolish and offensive 
sachs said but he said icahn apparently was trying to rationalize 
his negotiating strategy of demanding more cuts from the attendants 
the judge said the real reason icahn made a more generous offer 
to the machinists was because that union could do greater damage 
to twa in a strike and because icahn believed it would be easier 
to replace the attendants with untrained workers 
there has been no persuasive showing that sex stereotyping 
governed or influenced icahns economic demands only his 
rationalizations sachs said 
greedy employers like greedy unions have a legal right to 
try their strength and to enforce demands through the collective 
bargaining process the judge said 
the 8th us circuit court of appeals upheld the judges ruling 
last june 
the justices last year made it easier for workers to win suits 
against employers accused of sexual stereotyping but that decision 
was based on a federal civil rights law banning workplace 
discrimination not the railway labor act at issue in the case 
acted on today 
the case is independent federation of flight attendants vs twa 
89783 
