court of appeals that could have led to the refunds 
justice byron r white last week granted a temporary stay of the 
appeals court ruling and the courts order today extended that 
stay until it acts on a formal appeal to be filed by the energy 
companies 
the new orleansbased appeals court last sept 16 invalidated a 
4yearold federal regulation that allowed gas producers to raise 
some prices 
the appeals court ruled that the federal energy regulatory 
commission exceeded its authority in 1986 when permitting producers 
of old gas to raise their prices and to stop selling to 
pipeline companies not willing to pay the higher prices 
old gas is from wells that were producing before nov 9 1978 
congress that year approved a partial decontrol of the natural 
gas industry oldgas prices remained controlled but no caps were 
imposed on the price of gas from new wells 
the commissions 1986 regulation known as order 451 allowed 
the ceiling price of old gas to rise from 52 cents per thousand 
cubic feet to 275 
consumers distributors and pipeline companies challenged order 
451 leading to the 5th circuit court ruling 
in seeking emergency help lawyers for the energy companies said 
they would soon file a formal appeal seeking to overturn the 
appeals court decision which they said casts into doubt hundreds 
of gassupply contracts signed since 1986 
the justices were told that if the september ruling takes effect 
it will generate numerous contract disputes and introduce a 
period of great uncertainty in the entire natural gas market all 
during the winter heating season 
the case is mobil oil exploration v united distribution 
companies a503 
