<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
that a state may ban pharmacists from selling prescription drugs at 
a discount 
the court without comment rejected a challenge to a new jersey 
law banning drug discounts and rebates except for medications sold 
to people over 62 
the new jersey supreme court ruled last august that the law 
attacked as a form of economic protectionism has rational purposes 
and therefore is constitutional 
restricting prescription discounts prevents potentially 
destructive price wars that could erode the integrity of 
pharmaceutical services the state court said 
the state court also ruled that it is reasonable to discourage 
people from shopping around at different drug stores for the best 
buy saying that could undermine the use of socalled drug profiles 
the profiles are kept on file by some pharmacists to check for 
possible allergic reactions or use of incompatible prescription 
drugs by customers 
even if a court cannot ascertain the actual purpose of the 
statute it should sustain the statute if it has any conceivable 
rational purpose the state court said 
the law was challenged by consumer value stores cvs a chain 
that in 1985 advertised a special oneweek 3 price for most 
prescription drugs at its stores in wayne nj 
timothy brophy a pharmacist at a cvs store in wayne was fined 
500 by the new jersey pharmaceutical board 
the drug store chain said the ban on discounts discriminates 
against cutrate pharmacies and hurts economic competition the 
chain said the law is designed for the economic protection of a 
limited group in a profession whose lobby in a state legislature is 
more effective or more powerful than the lobby of others in the 
profession 
the law is irrational because customers 62 and older who are 
more likely to need medication are not afforded the presumed 
protection of banning discounts cvs said 
consumers are entitled to purchase prescription drugs at a 
pharmacy of their choice without undue influence from the state 
lawyers for the store said 
the new jersey supreme court said exempting senior citizens from 
the ban on discounts is a reasonable legislative response to 
economic pressure on the elderly 
the case is consumer value stores vs board of pharmacy 89801 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

