the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether nonprofit social clubs that are generally exempt from 
federal income taxes can use losses incurred from selling food and 
drink to nonmembers to offset investment profits 
the court said it will hear an appeal by the portland golf club 
in oregon in which at least 4 million in tax revenue nationwide is 
at stake 
the bush administration urged the justices to use the golf 
clubs appeal to settle a conflict between two federal appeals 
courts 
the golf club is exempt from paying federal income tax on dues 
and other fees paid by its members it qualifies for the exemption 
as a social club organized for pleasure recreation and other 
nonprofitable purposes 
but the club also receives income from selling food and drink to 
nonmembers and in interest from its investments that income is 
not exempt from federal taxation 
the internal revenue service said the golf club owed 5298 in 
taxes for 1980 and 1981 
the club said it lost 98041 those two years from selling food 
and drink to nonmembers because its expenses and overhead for that 
activity exceeded income from the sales 
the club sought to use the losses to offset profits from its 
investments 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals ruled in june that the 
losses are not deductible because the club had not intended the 
sale of food and drink to nonmembers to be a profitmaking 
activity 
that ruling conflicted with a decision in another case by the 
6th us circuit court of appeals 
the justice department said the supreme court should resolve the 
conflict it said there have been several hundred irs audits over 
the issue involving about 4 million 
the case is portland golf club vs commissioner of internal 
revenue 89530 
