the supreme court today curtailed an illinois 
public nuisance law that has been used to shut down adult 
bookstores and theaters for up to a year 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that the state 
law sometimes violates the freespeech rights of bookstore and 
theater owners 
the high court ruled in a new york case in 1986 that states may 
close down for long periods adult bookstores found to be public 
nuisances because of the onpremises conduct of their patrons 
but the illinois law in the case acted on today was more 
sweeping it permitted closing such stores and theaters if the 
operators were convicted of selling obscene material 
the illinois law said the establishment could either be closed 
or could be allowed to remain open if the owners posted a bond that 
would be forfeited if obscene material was sold on the premises 
the case stemmed from an attempted crackdown against the denmark 
ii bookstore in kendall county ill the building was leased by 
bruce and cathy riemenschneider to sequoia books inc 
there were numerous obscenity prosecutions against the bookstore 
from 1982 to 1985 resulting in eight guilty verdicts but the 
store remained open for business 
then in 1986 the state sought to declare the bookstore a public 
nuisance and a judge ordered it shut down for one year unless 
sequoia books posted a 5000 bond the bond was posted but the 
judge ruled that obscene magazines then were sold at the store and 
the bond was revoked 
the illinois supreme court ruled last march that the 
antinuisance law was unconstitutional 
the state argues that the sale of obscene material is the 
equivalent of the sexual conduct involved in the 1986 case 
decided by the supreme court the state court said we do not 
agree that the sale of obscene material and actual sexual conduct 
can be so easily equated 
the illinois court said states may not shut down establishments 
that sell nonobscene material merely because some obscene works 
have been sold 
this blunderbuss approach is inconsistent with our 
traditional insistence that the regulation of any form of 
expression even of obscenity be carefully drawn so as not to 
impact unduly upon protected speech the state court said 
the justices had a similar question under study in a dallas case 
decided last week 
in that case the court left unanswered whether anyone convicted 
of certain crimes may be barred from operating a sexually oriented 
business 
instead the high court struck down that part of the dallas 
ordinance requiring all sexually oriented businesses to acquire 
special licenses because of inadequate safeguards against licensing 
delays 
the case acted on today is illinois vs sequoia books 881844 
