against protesters who ransacked the capitals secret police 
headquarters national police chief dieter winderlich said today 
the announcement came hours after east germanys ruling 
communists said the storming of the building monday showed the 
countrys street revolution could get out of hand 
winderlich told a news conference that protesters also had 
broken into the buildings section for counterespionage activities 
but did not discover the identity of the sections workers 
he said the protesters caused hundreds of thousands of dollars 
in damage to the eightstory building 
the building today remained under control of an oppositionled 
citizens committee regular police officers and government 
representatives 
also today workers at a stateowned factory in the city of gera 
staged a politically motivated warning strike to show their 
dissatisfaction with the communists according to west berlins 
rias radio station 
in bonn the conservative daily newspaper die welt said soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev was expected to visit east berlin in 
the next two or three weeks 
die welt quoting wellinformed sources in east berlin said 
gorbachev plans a massive show of support for his longtime 
friend east german communist premier hans modrow 
dirk bachmann east berlins police chief said opposition 
groups calls for restraint had prevented injuries during the 
storming of the secret police building 
the protesters demanded the ouster of the communists and 
expressed anger at the government for not moving faster to 
dismantle the secret police and carry out reforms 
three months after a peaceful popular revolt toppled old 
hardline communist leaders the party still essentially controls 
the government media economy and bureaucracy 
the communist party daily newspaper neues deutschland said in a 
commentary that the organizers of protests like that at the secret 
police headquarters must accept responsibility for the consequences 
responsibility also means means having a clear idea about 
consequences before calling for a demonstration so that things 
dont get out of hand the newspaper said in a frontpage 
editorial 
it added the call for no violence which has marked the 
street revolution from the start becomes a farce when emotions 
break through the bounds of reason 
opposition leaders called for calm and an end to the destruction 
a day earlier new forum opposition group called for the 
protests to oppose what it called the restoration policy of 
communists seeking to gain an advantage before the may elections 
according to the official news agency adn 
the call was answered by hundreds of thousands of people 
including those who stormed the secret police headquarters 
dozens of protesters in the southern city of cottbus had pelted 
the local secret police building with rocks and unsuccessfully 
tried to enter it 
official news media also reported that about 500000 people 
demonstrated against the communists and secret police in at least a 
dozen cities on monday evening 
addressing the crowd at the berlin secret police headquarters 
through a loudspeaker system modrow asked the protesters to stay 
in a dialogue with his shaky coalition government and expressed 
full understanding for the rage caused by decades of repression 
at the hands of the secret police 
hours earlier modrow had offered opposition groups a far 
greater say in running the caretaker government before democratic 
elections on may 6 
the protest actions are reaching further into virtually all 
parts of society and even all age groups increasingly children 
and older adults in their 50s and 60s are joining in 
east germanys staterun television interrupted its programs 
several times to broadcast a warning against further actions like 
that in east berlin 
the democracy that is just now developing is in the gravest 
danger it warned 
government officials at talks with the opposition monday morning 
had outlined a chilling array of rifles rocketpropelled grenades 
and machine guns controlled by the secret police 
the disclosures which were broadcast live included news that 
the secret police consumed more than 1 percent of the national 
budget 
