<TEXT>
the united states expressed concern today 
over civilian casualties in three weeks of fighting between 
liberian soldiers and opponents of president samuel k doe 
we deplore actions whether by government troops or 
insurgents which lead to such casualties said a statement 
issued by the us embassy in monrovia the liberian capital 
sporadic fighting was reported today as government troops 
continued a search for rebels who said they have launched another 
offensive 
as far as we know there is still some fighting going on a 
western diplomat said in a telephone interview from monrovia 
the us embassy statement said officials had discussed the 
fighting with governments in the region but did not elaborate 
it also said officials were encouraging humanitarian groups 
including the international committee of the red cross and the un 
high commissioner for refugees to help an estimated 20000 people 
who have fled the fighting 
the government says the rebels who allegedly came from ivory 
coast on dec 24 killed 200 civilians before government troops 
brought the situation under control 
liberian authorities say 16 government officials were also 
killed after the rebels attacked the villages of butuo and karnplay 
near the border 
but two major human rights groups africa watch of new york and 
amnesty international of london have accused the military of also 
killing unarmed civilians 
jenkins scott liberias justice minister said last week that 
soldiers killed some civilians but insisted they acted in 
selfdefense 
amnesty international quoted refugees and other sources as 
saying hundreds of civilian were killed by the rebels and the 
military 
amnesty international said the fighting has forced 20000 
liberians to flee to ivory coast and guinea 
president houphouetboigny of ivory coast said earlier this 
month that between 8000 and 10000 people had entered his country 
charles taylor the selfproclaimed leader of the liberian 
dissidents told the british broadcasting corp today his forces 
had launched a new offensive south of the site of previous fighting 
the bbc made no mention of where its correspondent interviewed 
taylor a former liberian civil servant taylor gave no indication 
of the size of the new offensive 
the government says it has captured 11 of an estimated 100 
rebels who entered the country in two groups dec 24 and is seeking 
the remainder 
robert morris liberias assistant information minister 
declined to answer questions from the associated press 
liberia was founded in 1842 by freed american slaves 
president doe is a former master sergeant in the liberian army 
who came to power in a 1980 bloody coup last months invasion was 
the second attempt to oust doe in four years 
