<TEXT>
chinas communist party today called for fiscal 
austerity until at least 1991 outlined tough measures to lower the 
boom on nonessential industries and acknowledged that more 
workers will lose their jobs 
the plan reflects the current conservative leaderships drive to 
revive state controls over the economy which were loosened during 
the previous 10 years of reform and decentralization 
it also underscores the desire to give priority to the 
development of large staterun industries the party said some 
factories in particular smaller private enterprises will be 
closed during the austerity drive 
the plan which also urges controls on consumer demand was put 
foward in a lengthy party document on economic readjustment 
the policy paper carried by the official xinhua news agency does 
not mention any plans to introduce new marketoriented reforms 
reforms have effectively been put on hold since austerity 
policies were first adopted in fall 1988 and particularly after the 
ouster of proreform party leader zhao ziyang when prodemocracy 
protests were crushed in june 
the 39point document made public today was prepared for a 
plenary session of the party central committee in november it has 
apparently been circulated to party offices 
it says the task of restoring order to the economy that began in 
fall 1988 would take three years or more the paper also said the 
nations spending habits must be sharply curtailed during that time 
the party which under zhao was moving toward a policy of 
noninterference in economic affairs must enhance its leading role 
in guiding the economy the document said 
it said the nations economic goals are to bring the inflation 
rate under 10 percent a year keep annual growth of the gross 
national product to 56 percent keep new currency issues down and 
balance the budget the gross national product is the total worth 
of all goods and services 
china achieved some of those goals in 1989 bringing inflation 
down from a high of more than 30 percent in 1988 to less than 10 
percent in the final months of 1989 
however the governments tight credit and suspension of 
thousands of building projects have led to widespread bankruptcies 
plant shutdowns and a growing unemployment problem 
in the plan the party acknowledged that some workers will 
become unemployed 
china says the urban unemployment rate is approaching 4 percent 
up from 2 percent before the austerity drive the figures do not 
include millions of rural residents without work because of the 
slowdown 
the government has also fallen further into debt because of 
decreased revenues and huge subsidies provided faltering staterun 
factories 
todays report said smaller township enterprises the backbone 
of economic progress in rural areas during the past decade will 
not be allowed to vie with large industries for raw materials 
the plan said private enterprises are a necessary supplement to 
the socialist economy but must develop within the limits of state 
control 
</TEXT>
