<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken tuesday by the supreme court 
 
child abuse 
 
the court agreed to decide whether people accused of child abuse 
have the right to at least one facetoface confrontation with 
their young accusers 
the justices in two cases of enormous importance for 
childabuse prosecutions nationwide said they will consider 
reinstating the childmolesting conviction of a maryland daycare 
center owner and an idaho womans childabuse conviction 
the cases are maryland vs craig 89478 and idaho vs wright 
89260 
 
federal lands 
 
the court said it will consider limiting the power of 
environmentalists to prevent the opening up of federal lands to 
commerical development 
the court voted to review a proenvironmentalist ruling 
challenged by the bush administration the case involves a us 
circuit court of appeals ruling last june that the national 
wildlife federation may sue the interior department over plans to 
change the status of some 180 million acres of public land in 
western states and alaska 
the case is lujan vs national wildlife federation 89640 
 
police tips 
 
the court agreed to decide what authority police have to stop 
and question someone on the basis of an anonymous tip that the 
person is involved in a crime 
the justices said they will review an alabama court ruling that 
limited such police tactics 
the case is alabama vs white 89789 
 
sex assaults 
 
the court refused to kill lawsuits against two pennsylvania 
school officials by two former students who say they were sexually 
assaulted by their high school band instructor 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that the 
officials are not entitled to qualified legal immunity from being 
sued by the two former students 
the cases are smith vs stoneking 89780 and smith vs sowers 
89782 
 
eastern strike 
 
the court refused to let a machinists union strike against 
eastern airlines spread to commuter railroads 
the justices without comment left intact rulings barring 
sympathy strikes against railroads in new york city philadelphia 
and their suburbs 
the cases are international association of machinists vs long 
island railroad 89427 and 89674 and brotherhood of railroad 
signalmen vs septa 89756 
 
gas prices 
 
the court blocked indefinitely the effect of a lower court 
ruling that could have provided natural gas consumers with tens of 
millions of dollars in refunds 
the justices granting an emergency request by 21 energy 
companies held in abeyance a 5th us circuit court of appeals 
decision that could have led to the refunds 
the case is mobil oil exploration vs united distribution 
companies a503 
 
gas consumers 
 
the court agreed to consider broadening the power of states to 
sue in behalf of gas consumers allegedly overcharged by utility 
companies 
the court said it will hear an appeal by kansas and missouri 
officials who have accused utilities of illegal pricefixing 
the case is kansas vs kansas power amp light 882109 
 
twa 
 
the court turned away an appeal by trans world airlines flight 
attendants who accused twa owner carl icahn of sex bias in seeking 
wage cuts and other concessions that triggered a strike 
the court without comment refused to revive a lawsuit against 
the airline the flight attendants sought back pay and other 
benefits 
the case is independent federation of flight attendants vs twa 
89783 
 
church universal 
 
the court left intact a 156 million award against a montana 
religious group sued by a former member 
the court without comment rejected arguments that the award 
violates the religious freedom of the church universal amp triumphant 
the case is church universal amp triumphant vs witt 89672 
 
cable television 
 
the court left intact a ruling that cities may fine cable 
television companies for failing to broadcast enough locally 
originated programs 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by three 
affiliated chicago cable tv firms that said their freespeech 
rights were violated when they were fined 60750 
the case is chicago cable communications vs chicago cable 
commission 89747 
 
druggists 
 
the court let stand a ruling that a state may ban pharmacists 
from selling prescription drugs at a discount 
the court without comment rejected a challenge to a new jersey 
law banning drug discounts and rebates except for medication sold 
to people over 62 
the new jersey supreme court ruled last august that the law 
attacked as a form of economic protectionism has rational purposes 
and therefore is constitutional 
the case is consumer value stores vs board of pharmacy 89801 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

