<TEXT>
the publication of the koran in comicbook form 
drew more fire from islamic groups as the leading religious body of 
tunisia called for it to be banned as an impious work 
in a statement made public in tunis on monday the higher 
islamic council said the comic book if the koran were told to 
me which has been published in france has brought prejudice 
against the sanctity of the koran and moslems 
the illustration of the teachings of the holy koran by profane 
images constitutes sacrilege and heresy the statement said 
the koran is the sacred book of islam according to moslems it 
contains the words of god as revealed to the prophet mohammed 
the comic books are the work of youssef seddik a tunisianborn 
academic who has lived in paris since 1983 he was in tunis and not 
immediately available for comment according to his wife saida 
seddik 46 said in an interview earlier this month that his 
goal was simply to make the koran more accessible to young people 
and not to violate the sacredness of islam 
the tunisian religious body condemned seddik for not having 
consulted experts in islamic jurisprudence before publishing the 
comic books and appealed to islamic groups and the publishing world 
to act efficiently so as to prevent the repetition of such acts 
and thus preserve the inviolability of the sacredness of islam 
the series of comic books was criticized last week by mohammed 
faidallah head of islamic jurisprudence at kuwait university as 
ridiculing the sanctity of the holy koran 
he was quoted as calling seddik a new salman rushdie the 
indianborn british novelist condemned to death last year by the 
late ayotollah ruhollah khomeini for the satanic verses 
rushdie has been in hiding ever since 
my husband was completely astounded by the fact that people 
are comparing him to rushdie mrs seddik said tuesday he 
expected some people not to like it but he never dreamed he would 
be accused of blasphemy 
the comic book illustrations are accompanied by exact quotations 
from the koran complete with chapter and verse references 
