<TEXT>
the supreme court was urged tuesday to help 
consumers and to foster business competition by allowing states and 
private citizens to use federal antitrust law to break up corporate 
mergers 
the california attorney generals office argued that the clayton 
act passed in 1914 when congress was preoccupied with trust 
busting on a national scale empowers the state to challenge a 25 
billion merger of the lucky and alpha beta supermarket chains 
less competition in the industry leading to higher grocery 
bills for consumers will result from the merger said deputy 
california attorney general h chester horn jr 
the injury threatened by this merger is precisely the one the 
clayton act was designed to prevent he said 
but rex e lee representing the supermarket chains said only 
the federal government is empowered by the 1914 law to force 
divestiture in a completed merger 
justice sandra day oconnor said most of these mergers are 
handled before a state or private person knows the acquisition is 
taking place 
she asked lee whether he believed therefore that states and 
individuals would be powerless under federal law to break up such 
mergers 
that is exactly what congress intended lee replied it is 
is the change in status we are talking about from two independent 
companies to a unified structure he said 
breaking up the structure is something the federal 
government can do and no one else lee said 
lucky californias largest supermarket chain and alpha beta 
the fourth largest operate 550 stores between them 
alpha betas parent company american stores acquired lucky in 
june 1988 to merge the two chains under the lucky name 
american stores said california customers would save more than 
40 million a year because of increased efficiency but the 
california attorney generals office said the merger will mean less 
competition and will lead to 440 million in higher prices each 
year 
us district judge david kenyon in los angeles temporarily 
blocked the merger in 1988 and ordered continued separate operation 
of the two chains pending further court action 
but the 9th us circuit court of appeals overturned the judges 
ruling 
the appeals court said the state had it moved quickly enough 
could have prevented the merger but the appeals court said only 
the federal government has the power to break up completed mergers 
the federal trade commission temporarily blocked the acquisition 
in 1988 but later reached an agreement with the corporations 
allowing the deal as long as certain conditions were met 
much of the hourlong arguments before the high court tuesday 
focused on the intentions of the clayton acts drafters 76 years 
ago 
lee referred to testimony before a congressional committee by 
louis d brandeis a lawyer who represented president wilsons 
administration two years before brandeis was appointed to the 
supreme court 
brandeis made it clear the administration was proposing 
legislation that would give the federal government and no one else 
power to dissolve a merger lee said 
but horn argued that brandeis and the congressmen were 
discussing a much different bill than the one that was introduced 
and became the clayton act 
brandeis was saying only that the power to attack the 
nationwide trusts belonged in the hands of the federal 
government not other corporate mergers horn said 
the case is california vs american stores 89258 
