answer simeonov told the communists seated across the table in 
the west hall of the national parliament 
our slogans and our ideas do not reach everybody we want what 
we have to say to be heard by everyone simeonov said 
access to the media is important in bulgaria which is isolated 
from western and all east bloc broadcasts but soviet ones and 
whose staterun media continue to run vitriolic attacks on 
opposition figures in an attempt to discredit them with the public 
the opposition won agreement on the daily newspaper which it 
hopes will have a print run of some 50000 copies 
opposition spokesman georgi spassov declined to say who would 
write for it or exactly when it would start to appear as the 
countrys first independent daily since the communists repressed 
all opposition in 1947 
the disarray that marked the talks was played out for an hour in 
front of bulgarian and foreign journalists and illustrated the 
difficulties of east europeans trying to move from totalitarian 
rule to more democracy without tools basic for the transition 
spassov noted that almost all buildings in bulgaria are 
controlled by the state thus putting the opposition in the 
position of begging the authorities for office space and a 
telephone 
plainly speaking we cannot exist simeonov told the 
communists 
he asked how the opposition could be members of the negotiations 
when we have no way of meeting to discuss things beforehand the 
conditions are unfavorable as if on purpose 
andrei lukanov the powerful and politically skilled no 2 to 
communist party chief and president petar mladenov argued the 
ruling party had done all it could to provide offices and 
newsprint he said matters were no longer in the communists hands 
i dont think you should be so suspicious he said with a 
smile to the opposition many of whom were jailed for months or 
years by the communists 
the two sides eventually reached agreement during a closeddoor 
session 
although the oppositions demand for live radio and television 
broadcast of the talks and direct access to the electronic media 
was rejected long excerpts of the session were shown on the 
evening tv news 
according to a tentative schedule the talks are supposed to 
discuss the transition to democracy and the free elections mladenov 
has promised by may the talks are scheduled to resume thursday 
the opposition seeks twostage legislative elections in may and 
november arguing they wont have enough time or resources to 
organize an adequate campaign against the communists by may 
the communists meanwhile seem to be trying to preserve as much 
power as possible hoping they can avoid the massive loss in 
authority suffered by their comrades everywhere else in eastern 
europe 
at least three recognizable factions have formed inside the 
communist party which on jan 30 holds a national congress that 
reformers hope will see the final purge of orthodox loyalists 
supporting todor zhivkov the hardline communist leader ousted 
nov 10 after 35 years in power 
some analysts believe the communists are encouraging the 
formation of reformist factions in order to attract more votes 
diplomats who asked not to be identified say the opposition is 
growing fast as well with the social democratic party among the 
fastest growing groups 
most of the social democrats leaders were jailed and some even 
killed by the communists in the late 1940s but in a never 
explained oversight the party was not banned and is said to be 
attracting tens of thousands of new members 
</TEXT>
