<TEXT>
some major corporations are making significant 
cuts in their use of three ozonedestroying chemicals but the 
vast majority of companies have yet to take any concrete steps to 
phase them out a private environmental group said tuesday 
the natural resources defense council produced industry figures 
showing that more than 200 million pounds of the three chemicals 
which are primarily used as metalcleaning solvents had been 
released into the atmosphere by more than 3000 companies in 1987 
the figures were the latest comprehensive ones available 
responses to questionnaires sent by the group by more than 300 
companies indicate that while some large polluters have reduced 
their use of the chemicals and emissions others have not 
their delays threaten the health and safety of all 
americans maintained david doniger an attorney for the 
washingtonbased environmental group 
the chemicals examined by the group are methyl chloroform and 
cfc113 both of which are widely used by electronics computer and 
aerospace industries as metalcleaning solvents and carbon 
tetrachloride used in the united states primarily in the 
manufacture of chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs 
the three chemicals are among those that when released can drift 
high into the atmosphere where the chlorine component reacts with 
the earths protective ozone layer destroying the ozone past 
emissions of the three chemicals currently account for more than a 
third of the chlorine attacking the ozone layer which protects the 
earth from ultraviolet rays 
government and industry have acknowleged that the cfcs 
including cfc113 used as a solvent and carbon tetrachloride should 
be phased out and expect their elimination by the middle or latter 
part of the decade 
but methyl chloroform whose potency for ozone destruction is 
less than 15 percent that of cfcs remains unregulated and is 
viewed by much of industry as a potential bridge chemical as 
companies stop using cfcs as cleaning solvents 
methyl chloroform is part of the solution to the depletion of 
stratospheric ozone not part of the problem argued keith 
mckennon president of dow chemical usa in a letter to the 
environmental group 
dow manufactures about half of the methyl chloroform produced in 
the united states two other leading manufacturers ppg industries 
inc and vulcan chemical corp made similar arguments saying 
the chemical should not be banned from use 
but environmentalists contend that while the poundforpound 
destructiveness of methyl chloroform may be far less than cfcs the 
chemicals widespread use causes it to be of equal concern 
it is part of the problem doniger said at a news 
conference arguing that without curbs on methyl chloroform use 
you cant get the chlorine reductions needed after the year 
2000 to reverse the destruction of the ozone layer 
decisions made in the boardrooms of these companies using the 
chemicals will determine whether we succeed or fail in preventing 
the first truly global environmental catastrophe doniger 
continued 
some major users of the ozonedepleting chemicals have begun to 
make sizeable cuts in the use of the three chemicals however 
according to figures provided by the group 
for example pratt amp whitney the aircraft engine manufacturer 
in east hartford conn was reported to release 19 million pounds 
of methyl chloroform more than any other facility in 1987 but 
reported cutting emissions to 420000 pounds in 1988 
ibm corp one of the biggest users of cfc113 three years ago 
cut its emissions of the chemical at three plants in california 
new york and minnesota by nearly onethird from 33 billion pounds 
in 1987 to 23 billion pounds in 1988 its emissions of methyl 
chloroform also declined from 16 million pounds to 12 million 
pounds according to the figures from the environmental group 
hercules inc was the leading source of carbon tetrachloride 
emissions 1987 and again in 1988 when it spewed nearly 900000 
pounds of the chemical into the air from a parlin nj facility 
but the company said it stopped using the chemical altogether in 
august 1989 
but scores of smaller companies reported increases in emissions 
as did atampt technologies inc at lees summit mo where combined 
cfc113 and methyl chloride emissions increased by about 40000 
pounds to 744000 pounds in 1988 one of the highest amounts for 
any facility that year 
atampt has announced a corporatewide goal of eliminting its 
reliance on cfcs as a cleaning solvent by the mid1990s 
</TEXT>
