<TEXT>
mexican authorities are looking into claims 
that a murdered us drug enforcement administration agent was 
actually in league with drug traffickers mexicos attorney general 
said tuesday 
at a memorial service for 44 mexican narcotics agents killed in 
the line of duty attorney general enrique alvarez del castillo 
said mexican officials had no independent corroboration of press 
reports that the dea agent enrique camarena was corrupt 
we are checking the basis of those reports said alvarez 
who refused to give further details in a brief encounter with 
reporters 
the reports which involved marijuana busts in northwestern 
mexico surfaced last week after the broadcast of the nbctv 
miniseries drug wars based on camarenas murder in 1985 by top 
mexican drug traffickers 
us officials have denied camarena was corrupt in any way 
noting the charges were old and never backed by any evidence 
the miniseries which showed corrupt mexican officials aiding 
narcotics traffickers and thwarting the investigation of camarenas 
murder caused controversy in mexico comments on nbc news programs 
that followed the miniseries angered mexicans by suggesting the 
corruption that killed camarena still exists 
alvarezs remarks overshadowed a speech by president carlos 
salinas de gortari to 400 law enforcement officials and relatives 
of the dead officers in which salinas vowed to press the fight 
against official corruption 
the first condition for attacking narcotics trafficking is to 
dismantle and destroy the networks of corruption that protect it 
salinas said 
salinas has made an effort to remove drug trafficking as an 
irritant in usmexico relations winning praise from us 
officials for vigorously pursuing drug traffickers 
such pursuit has resulted in the seizure of 36 tons of cocaine 
in the 13 months salinas has been in office more than was seized 
the previous 10 years 
nevertheless the government newspaper el nacional published a 
frontpage story friday that quoted anonymous sources as saying 
camarena had been murdered because he had betrayed the drug 
traffickers he worked for 
dea spokesman frank shultz in washington said there was not a 
scintilla of evidence whatsoever that enrique camarena was involved 
with the traffickers in any way other than an adversarial role 
elaine shannon author of the book desperados on which the 
miniseries was based said mexican authorities began attacking 
camarenas integrity in 1985 in order to divert attention from 
themselves and even tried to set up a fake bank account to prove 
camarena took dirty money 
its rather sad that the mexican government is reduced to this 
transparent attempt at slander rather than to try to improve their 
governments own ability to enforce their laws protect their 
citizens and bring drug traffickers and the people who killed 
camarena to justice shannon said 
kingpins rafael caro quintero and ernesto fonseca carrillo were 
sentenced in december to 40 years in prison without parole for the 
camarena murder but many us officials believe the full story has 
not been told 
the memorial ceremony at mexico citys airport was hastily 
arranged to demonstrate mexicos commitment to the fight against 
drug trafficking following the jan 7 8 and 9 drug wars 
broadcasts 
meanwhile a mexican advertising group bought fullpage ads in 
the washington post the new york times and the los angeles times 
to outline mexicos antidrug efforts the ads cost a total of 
124340 
drug wars itself appeared in english on mexico citys cable 
tv system and a mexican network broadcast a program sunday that 
purported to expose the programs errors and included mention of 
the accusations against camarena 
nbc has defended the program and its reporting since then 
mexican officials say the controversy will not affect working 
relations between the two governments especially in narcotics 
we do not deny our problems nor do we look for excuses for 
our errors salinas said 
although the great majority of our agents have demonstrated 
great valor in fighting drug trafficking i repeat we will 
energetically punish those who involve themselves in drug 
trafficking he said 
salinas promises to fight corruption were given an added edge 
by the arrest of four mexico city police officers on rape charges 
the attorney generals office refused to comment on published 
reports at least three of the accused had been bodyguards for 
javier coello trejo the assistant attorney general in charge of 
the fight against drug traffickers 
