<TEXT>
gun control advocates tuesady marked the first 
anniversary of the massacre of five california schoolchildren by 
announcing they want a government ban on imports of semiautomatic 
assaultstyle pistols 
these are killing machines said susan whitmore of handgun 
control inc adding that the organization will petition the 
government wednesday to eliminate imports of such pistols as the 
uzi and the hk94 shorter versions of assaultstyle rifles banned 
last summer 
among the 43 types of assaultstyle rifle imports banned last 
july was the popular ak47 model used by 24yearold drifter 
patrick purdy to kill five children and wound 29 others and a 
teacher on jan 17 1989 at a school playground in stockton calif 
but the treasury departments bureau of alcohol tobacco and 
firearms as well as the national rifle association say banning the 
imports of the pistols will be a lot more difficult than the 
banning of the rifles 
the handgun regulations in place for the past two decades were 
intended to rule out cheap saturday night specials not 
wellmade sophisticated assaultstyle weapons said atf spokesman 
jack killorin 
those handguns that met the criteria atf established after 
congress approved the gun control act of 1968 including such 
things as barrel length round size overall length and weight 
have been considered to have met the sporting use requirement 
imposed on all imports he said 
the atf had more leeway to ban imports of the semiautomatic 
assaultstyle rifles because in essence a new form of weapon had 
appeared that had been relatively unexamined under the law now 
you look at the issue of handguns and the degree to which that has 
been examined this is an area that doesnt lack examination 
it has been established and in practice for over 20 years 
because of the extensive legislative history and longstanding 
regulations for handgun imports it would be much more difficult 
for us to ban certain handgun imports he said 
i dont know how one would design criteria that would exclude 
the firearms theyre talking about and not exclude all the other 
firearms said jim baker the nras director of governmental 
affairs i think that handgun control would like to ban anything 
that theres a political or emotional opportunity to ban and this 
is consistent with that policy 
but david g mengebier handgun controls legislative counsel 
who wrote the petition said that like the assaultstyle rifles 
banned last july the assaultstyle pistols also reflect new 
technology and a new situation that calls for new regulations not 
accounted for in the legislative history 
all of the factors which atf considered persuasive in banning 
the importation of semiautomatic assault rifles are present and 
applicable to semiautomatic assault pistols the petition says 
with the exception of their length semiautomatic assault 
pistols are identitical to semiautomatic assault rifles in terms 
of their evolutionary development design physical components and 
intended use the petition says 
killorin said the atf could look at how the pistols are being 
used in real life one of the things that drove the issue of the 
semiautomatic assault rifles were the astonishing numbers that 
were beginning to appear for importation we may take a look at how 
many of these are coming in these may not be a significant import 
item 
mengebier said in an interview that his organization has not 
been given access to import figures for 1989 because they are 
considered proprietary information but he said its safe to say 
that thousands have been authorized for importation or are being 
imported 
 
