<TEXT>
the survival of us television networks in 
the 1990s will depend on how they compete in a rapidly changing 
marketplace nbc president robert c wright told tv programmers 
tuesday 
the major broadcast networks are still locked into essentially 
one business and one traditional source revenue from 
advertisers wright said in the keynote address to the 27th 
annual gathering of the national association of television 
programming executives 
the cost of network programs is outpacing the growth of that 
revenue and 3 broadcast networks and 27 cable networks are 
bobbing around today in a modestly growing advertising 
marketplace 
networks will see more new competitors a diminished audience 
share and their very modest profit margins continue to shrink 
he said 
the boundaries are disappearing wright said but 
governmental regulations are forcing the networks to live behind 
televisions equivalent of the berlin wall 
he cited fox televisions emergence as a competing network and 
japanese electronics giant sony corps purchase of cbs records and 
columbia pictures 
movie studios buy tv stations and cable tv subsidiary turner 
communications has one of the largest tv and film libraries in the 
world 
against this backdrop the networks scream for freedom from 
the shackles of obsolete anticompetitive government 
regulations wright said 
specifically wright cited the federal communications 
commissions financialinterest syndication regulations known in 
the industry as finsyn or fisr 
the regulations bar nbc abc and cbs from having a financial 
interest in programs they dont produce themselves and also 
prohibits the networks from being in program syndication or sharing 
revenues from syndicated programs 
natpes annual meeting is the largest marketplace for syndicated 
programming in the world but the network presence is minimal 
the financial rules are an outgrowth of positions taken in the 
1960s they were intended to make the 1970s more competitive 
wright said 
in 1983 after four years of hearings the fcc federal trade 
commission and the commerce and justice departments concluded that 
the rules should be abolished he said political lobbying by the 
movie industry kept the rules alive he said 
letting the networks have a stake in entertainment programs 
would help networks pay the bill on news and sports and support 
network services to affiliates anything that restricts our 
ability to compete for quality entertainment programming also 
restricts the opportunity and profitability of more than 600 
networkaffiliated stations wright said 
financial interest doesnt guarantee us anything it only 
gives us an opportunity to produce and derive some ancillary 
benefit from our success on the air wright said 
wright in offering a series of predictions for the 1990s said 
the berlin wall of finsyn rules will collapse and fall under 
its own weight 
he also predicted that the creative financing techniques of 
movie making will move into tv production distributors 
producers exhibitors and syndicators will all have crossover 
interests and investments he said 
program standards will continue to stretch he said some 
services will do very nicely with programming that would be totally 
unacceptable on other networks he said the major networks will 
continue to meet the standards of most americans while others 
flirt with niche audiences who march to a different drummer 
wright said the 1990s will be an exciting decade for television 
with more programs needed to fit the growing array of services to 
the viewer 
less bureaucracy more entrepreneurship less history more 
future wright said the creative the patient the focused 
will survive the slow the encumbered and the backwardlooking 
will fail 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

