<TEXT>
the free speech rights of three illinois 
residents were violated when they were rejected for state jobs or 
promotions because they failed to support republicans an attorney 
told the supreme court on tuesday 
in a case that will determine whether partisanship must be put 
aside when public employers hire promote or transfer attorney 
mary lee leahy asked the justices to apply past rulings that ban 
firings 
jobs are important to people promotions are important to 
people mrs leahy said 
the state has an obligation to be neutral when granting the 
benefits that are stake in this case she said 
mrs leahy represents two men and a woman who say their job 
status suffered because they did not vote in republican primaries 
or give money to the party 
their lawsuit which had been thrown out by two lower courts 
targets gov james r thompson the republican party of illinois 
and leaders of several state agencies 
mrs leahy said the governors office has controlled all new 
hires since 1980 in her written brief to the court she included a 
form that is used to screen state employees who seek a promotion 
and live in sangamon county 
the form asks employees to declare how they or in some cases 
their parents voted in primary elections it also asks whether the 
person would be willing to work for republicans during an election 
the attorney for thompson and illinois republicans said 
officials followed the state personnel code which require tests 
when people apply for a job 
all the people who were hired or promoted qualified under the 
code attorney thomas p sullivan said 
but he also acknowledged that when officials examine the field 
of qualified candidates they might favor someone who has the same 
political stripe 
sullivan said that hiring political supporters stimulates good 
government because the employee is likely to appreciate the job 
and in turn serve the public well 
both attorneys were interrupted several times by the justices 
justice antonin scalia said many political scientists believe 
patronage simply is part of the spoils system and helps 
preserve the countrys twoparty system 
mrs leahy replied this is not a way to preserve a twoparty 
system but a oneparty system 
the supreme court in a 1980 ruling that significantly weakened 
patronage said government workers may not be fired solely because 
of their political affiliation unless that affiliation was an 
appropriate requirement of carrying out their jobs 
the court however did not address the issues raised in the 
illinois case hiring promotion and transfer 
the lead petitioner is cynthia rutan who has worked for the 
illinois department of rehabilitative services since 1974 she has 
applied for promotions but has not received one she also has not 
supported republicans unlike people who were promoted over her 
franklin taylor has worked for the illinois department of 
transportation as an equipment operator for 21 years he sought a 
promotion in 1983 and said he was rejected because he did not have 
an endorsement from fulton county republicans 
the third petitioner is james moore he said he has tried to get 
a state job particularly with the corrections department since 
1978 but has failed because he could not obtain the signatures of 
the pope county republican chairman and a local gop lawmaker 
