<TEXT>
washington state officials have tentatively 
concluded that chemicals put in tanks of radioactive waste at the 
hanford nuclear reservation do not pose a serious risk of 
explosion the states top health official said tuesday 
kristine gebbie secretary of the state department of health 
said preliminary results of a study by state health and ecology 
officials found no special hazard existed from the chemicals she 
said a conclusion had not been reached 
the existence of the chemical ferrocyanide in the waste tanks 
and the possibility that the mixture could trigger a massive 
explosion was detailed in a 1984 study for the energy department 
that was kept secret until last fall 
the chemical was added to the tanks in the mid1950s to help 
separate the radioactive metals from the liquid waste the wastes 
were generated by the hanford nuclear reactors which produced 
plutonium for the nations atomic weapons 
ms gebbie disclosed the states preliminary assessment of the 
potential hazard in response to questions from reporters after a 
meeting with energy secretary james d watkins ms gebbie is 
chairman of a panel of experts advising watkins on ways to 
restructure and improve the departments health research activities 
she provided no details of the preliminary study of the tank 
waste hazards 
