twenty masked and armed attackers on tuesday 
night rushed into a hut in a vietnamese boat people detention 
center and attacked those inside killing one and injuring seven 
police said wednesday 
police quickly brought the situation under control but no 
arrests were reported a police investigation was launched 
one of those injured was hospitalized 
a police source speaking on condition of anonymity said that 
because the detention center is a closed camp authorities believe 
the attackers are also boat people living in other huts 
in the past months many fights erupted in the camps with boat 
people using iron bars swords and lances as weapons 
about 56000 vietnamese boat people now are housed in squalid 
camps in hong kong about 12000 of them arrived before june 1988 
and are considered refugees eligible for resettlement but the rest 
arrived later and are being screened if they are classified as 
illegal immigrants they must either go home voluntarily or be 
repatriated by force to vietnam 
on dec 12 hong kong repatriated 51 boat people against their 
wishes 
in london on tuesday british lawmakers lord ennals and timothy 
raison said they found no evidence of force in that repatriation 
and no evidence that those sent back were persecuted on their 
return 
ennals and raison both former cabinet ministers said in a 
report that the involuntary return involved an element of 
overkill in the police presence and equipment used before departure 
and on board the aircraft 
however they said they reported finding no evidence of force 
being used and said it was the method of return to which the boat 
people objected 
the two visited vietnam last week at the british governments 
request 
they said they found in every case that the motives of the 51 
repatriates for going to hong kong were economic 
ennals told a news conference he was unhappy about further 
forcible repatriation raison said it was important to show 
vietnamese they could not go to hong kong a british colony in 
hopes of moving on elsewhere 
britain has decided that many boat people went to hong kong to 
seek a higher standard of living and not to escape political 
persecution 
