<TEXT>
the supreme court took a major step tuesday 
toward making its opinions quickly available via computer when it 
agreed to let a 24group consortium provide the necessary equipment 
the consortiums equipment will be used to disseminate the 
opinions to 10 to 15 media and legal organizations which will then 
relay the information more widely to newspapers law firms and 
other consumers 
the associated press is among the media organizations seeking 
middleman status as a distributor 
a court committee overseeing the project said it had accepted an 
offer from the supreme court opinion network scon and soon will 
begin discussions to determine what kind of equipment is needed 
scon a nonprofit consortium also includes as its members the 
american bar association cspan cable television network 
knightridder mead data united press international and the 
washington post 
the equipment will be provided free of charge under the courts 
ground rules the parties bidding for middlemen distribution rights 
had to be willing to supply the computer hardware and software 
west publishing co a major legal publisher had made an offer 
similar to scons 
fourteen groups earlier had proposed separate delivery systems 
and networks to the court the court turned down all previous 
proposals before deciding on this twoyear test which could begin 
as early as this spring and will be administered by the court 
the associated press which was among the 14 originally 
submitting proposals intends to receive the opinions 
electronically and make them available to its membership the 
details of the ap plan have not been made final pending further 
description of the courts system 
the court will choose 10 to 15 middleman subscribers that 
for a 500 annual fee will receive opinions electronically minutes 
after they are announced and distribute them the court describes 
these middlemen as mass disseminators of information 
the court committee said subscribers will be those 10 to 15 
organizations the court determines can best provide opinions to the 
broadest possible audience 
</TEXT>
