<TEXT>
a 5yearold centreville boy who fell 
through ice and was submerged for 40 minutes has only a slim chance 
for a full recovery one of the doctors treating him said tuesday 
police said george sader was playing with other children on the 
ice of a drainage pond in the washington suburb of centreville when 
it broke monday 
most of his major organs suffered from the insult of being 
without any oxygen and blood flow for a prolonged period of time 
said dr craig futterman a pediatric internist at fairfax hospital 
the boy requires quite a bit of effort to keep him stable 
futterman added 
among the organs damaged were the brain liver and lungs the 
doctor said were going to have problems with brain swelling 
his heart has done surprisingly well considering the 
circumstances futterman said 
he said the boy had a 1 to 2 percent chance of a full 
recovery 
another pediatrician gary kavit said it would be days or weeks 
before doctors could determine the extent of brain damage 
in recent years doctors have learned that young children often 
can survive prolonged periods submerged in cold water because their 
heartbeat and brain activity are drastically slowed the colder the 
water and the younger the child the better the chances of 
survival adults have lost the reflex that makes the bodily 
processes slow down 
though paramedics performed cpr cardiopulmonary resuscitation 
doctors were unable to start the boys heart once he arrived at the 
hospitals emergency room his body temperature was 90 degrees 
fahrenheit 
he was hooked up to a heartlung machine so his blood could be 
warmed outside the body 
two girls with young sader vivian daniel 12 and carol zakkak 
14 his cousin fell in trying to rescue him but were not seriously 
injured authorities said 
