<TEXT>
christian radio and television stations 
suspended their newscasts tuesday to protest a threat by christian 
gen michel aoun to close them down if they continue to refer to 
president elias hrawi as head of state 
voice of lebanon of the rightist phalange party and voice of 
free lebanon of the lebanese forces militia broadcast a directive 
from aoun saying the media should not refer to hrawi as president 
or to prime minister salim hoss as head of government 
the directive said hrawi was merely a former member of 
parliament and noted that the general declared the legislature 
dissolved nov 4 to prevent the election of a head of state 
after the broadcast the radio stations said they were 
suspending their hourly newscasts and abstaining from reporting 
the news until a way is found to cope with the new directive 
announcers at the stations indicated they viewed the directive 
as an attempt to gag the press and introduce censorship 
they were later joined by the lebanese broadcasting corp the 
nations widest viewed television station operated by the lebanese 
forces which said it was suspending its two evening newscasts 
until further notice 
the media in lebanon reflect a broad spectrum of political 
thought and take pride in being among the freest in the arab world 
despite the 14yearold moslemchristian civil war 
aoun issued the directive in his capacity as information 
minister of an interim military cabinet he has headed since sept 
22 1988 when president amin gemayels term expired with 
parliament unable to elect a successor 
he later summoned newspaper editors to the bunker of the 
presidential palace and said he would expel from the christian 
enclave anyone failing to abide by his directive broadcast editors 
were not called 
i am going to apply the law against anyone who doesnt abide 
by this directive if you want to refer to hrawi as the president 
