doru tigau a philosophy professor sat in 
a chair occupied until a few weeks ago by a niece of nicolae 
ceausescu he smoked an endless chain of cigarettes and talked 
about trying to run romanias revolution in an outofthe way place 
like iasi 
for the time being this is a nightmare he said there is 
a leadership in bucharest that isnt giving us instructions but 
giving us a general line 
but he has ideas 
everyone should take as much land as he and his family can 
work without hiring someone else to work for him he said a 
hardworking man can have everything but a lazy man has nothing or 
changes his job 
tigau 43 is the president of the 24member local branch of the 
national salvation front which has taken over communist party 
headquarters in iasi a city of 300000 people on the soviet border 
in his hands and in the hands of other local leaders like him 
may rest romanias future as a democracy 
after the euphoria of victory nutsandbolts administrative 
problems face inexperienced local leaders like tigau who are trying 
to turn an uprising against the leadership into a revolution in 
every aspect of society 
the revolution has no money but bills still must be paid 
there is no personal security but bands of ceausescus secret 
police have disappeared nervous soldiers keeping the peace 
mistakenly have threatened leaders of the revolution as well 
more than 200 ceausescu loyalists must be replaced in top 
government jobs in the region 
the revolt that led to nicolae ceausescus execution on 
christmas day went off quietly in iasi no bullet holes pock the 
walls of buildings and no memorials mark the places as they do in 
the capital bucharest where people fell to the gunfire of 
ceausescus personal guard 
now tigau is the leader of iasi presiding from the long 
paneled office where the local communist party leader ceausescus 
niece maria ghitulica once ran things 
up from his desk and pacing the floor to stay awake and still 
smoking tigau consulted with subordinates on selecting a new 
official to take responsibility for cultural affairs and he 
expounded on the need to put land back in the hands of peasants 
tigau said he never actively opposed the ceausescu leadership 
but expressed his opposition in trying to show his students the 
difference between reality and what the dictator preached 
across the border in soviet moldavia deputy premier mikhail s 
platon said in an interview that contacts with the new local 
leaders of iasi showed them to be enthusiastic but inexperienced 
they are young people he said 
one of the problems in iasi is that the revolution is without 
money the hundreds of volunteers racing busily around in the 
threestory party headquarters are not getting paid for it nor 
does the local national salvation front have any way of getting 
money 
while willing to help foreign visitors make longdistance 
telephone calls tigaus team insisted that the calls be paid for 
directly to the telephone exchange in local currency the lei so 
while an operator traveled from the telephone office to collect the 
money and then put through the call travelers dollars were taken 
to the local bank 
there as under the repressive ceausescu regime the serial 
numbers of the bills were registered before the bank handed over 
the official exchange of romanian currency 
but lodging in the main tourist hotel usually the equivalent in 
leis of about 30 a night was free 
you must not pay said a desk clerk named irina 
why not 
thats just the new rule 
after the revolution the supply of food improved in iasi 
georgetta agape a young sales clerk at a meat counter in an 
iasi food store said she no longer had to experience the shame of 
asking to see peoples identifications before she could sell them 
rationed meat 
for the first time in many years we had such delicacies as 
salami ham and pork she said but the store was sold out of 
them by nightfall 
even the unofficial price of kent cigarettes for years 
romanias unofficial black currency for the procurement of 
goods in great demand dropped dramatically from about 200 lei a 
pack 2270 at the stillprevailing official rate of exchange 
as kents went on sale in regular stores several people said 
the old communist party central committee headquarters is now 
guarded by soldiers with automatic weapons 
tigau recalled that he and the army captain in charge of 
security at the revolutionary headquarters were detained as they 
walked nearby at 430 one morning by anxious young soldiers manning 
an armored personnel carrier 
guns were taken away from the two and tigau recalled the young 
soldier asking the officer in charge what do we do now shoot 
them instead they were taken to the nearby palace of culture 
where cooler heads checked their identities and let them go 
another time a woman seeking a meeting with tigau in his office 
was found to be carrying a knife 
civilians unaccustomed to weapons that had been strictly 
controlled carried guns in the first days of the uprising adding 
to the uncertainty and tension 
mihai avadanei a teacher of english and a translator said in 
amazement im 48 years old and i was carrying a gun and i was 
ready to use it 
but in contrast to the heavy cordons of soldiers and 
paratroopers around leaders in the capital no security is provided 
for the new local leaders of the revolution or their families in 
iasi 
that compounds worries about the 200 members of ceausescus 
securitate secret police who were stationed in iasi and who local 
officials say disappeared after the revolt the army confiscated 
their weapons but many people believe that securitate had secret 
stocks hidden elsewhere 
the central committees stack of books by and about ceausescu 
are being gathered for disposal 
when tigau opened cabinets and the safe of mrs ghitulica 
ceausescus niece he said he found packages of foreignmade hose 
and womens underwear her communist party card 62000 lei in 
checks and a telegram from an unknown source appealing to iasi to 
