<TEXT>
the chapter 11 petition monday by campeau corps department 
store operations in the united states marked the biggest bankruptcy 
court filing ever for a retailer 
here is a brief look at campeau corp what happened and who is 
immediately affected 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
once a construction and real estate development company 
torontobased campeau corp became primarily known for acquiring 
federated department stores inc and allied stores corp in the 
united states where founder robert campeau gambled he could make 
an immense fortune the chains operate 258 stores throughout the 
country ranging from bloomingdales in the east to lazarus in the 
midwest and south to the bon marche in the west the immense debt 
the companies incurred in the buyout by campeau combined with 
disappointing retail sales crimped their ability to meet interest 
payments and merchandise bills 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
bank creditors led by citibank pressured campeau last month to 
show it could pay 234 billion in loans a fraction of its total 
obligations suppliers of credit and merchandise to campeau stores 
began to withhold delivery fearing they wouldnt get paid some 
employees and campeau stores reported local banks wouldnt cash 
their paychecks many observers speculated that bankruptcy court 
was the most logical strategy for allowing the retailing operations 
to remain open while the parent companies worked out a way to pay 
their debts 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law campeaus 
retailing units will get an immediate reprieve from creditor bills 
while a reorganization plan is devised to satisfy debts suppliers 
likely will resume or continue shipments confident they will be 
paid federated and allied said the stores will continue to operate 
as normal employees will still get pay and benefits and customer 
services credit card sales merchandise returns gift 
certificates for example would continue as normal a 
reorganization plan which might include the sale of some stores 
and all other major business moves must be approved by a bankruptcy 
judge 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
the 66yearold french canadian entrepreneur largely unknown in 
the united states until a few years ago made a fortune in 
construction and eventually became one of canadas biggest real 
estate developers he spent 10 billion much of it in borrowed 
money to buy allied stores corp and federated department stores 
inc confident the debt could be repaid despite widespread 
skepticism and a mixed outlook for the retailing industry 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

