<DOCNO> AP900116-0218 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
specialty chains will have an edge over mass 
merchandisers as the american retail industry adapts to changing 
consumer needs in the 1990s executives and economists say 
the days are numbered for giant retailers trying to be all 
things to all people stores without a sharp focus will lose 
customers while competitors making clear pitches to niches will 
gobble up market share according to views presented monday at the 
national retail merchants associations 79th annual convention 
and on a day when debtchoked campeau corp announced it was 
sheltering its us retailers in bankruptcy court industry 
executives predicted a bleak future for heavily leveraged store 
groups 
allied stores corp and federated department stores inc 
operators of many prominent us department stores were placed 
under court protection from creditors it was the largest filing 
under chapter 11 of the bankruptcy code ever made by a us 
retailer 
chains run by allied and federated accounting for nearly 260 
department stores will stay in business while a reorganization 
plan is plotted campeau took on a crushing debt burden when it 
bought federated for 66 billion in 1988 and allied for 34 
billion in 1986 
william r howell chairman and chief executive officer of jc 
penney co inc said it will become increasingly difficult for 
debtladen retailers with weak balance sheets to remain independent 
or even survive 
well continue to see a shakeout process in the years 
ahead he said at the convention held in a new york hotel the 
retail business has been hurt by overpriced mergers and by the 
resultant overleveraging of companies 
thomas e swanstrom chief economist of sears roebuck and co 
said some of the problems caused by the campeau crisis should 
subside in a few months 
campeaus desperation for cash late last year forced its stores 
to slash prices to attract customers and boost sales competing 
stores had to follow suit which pinched profits 
retailers face other challenges to profitability partly due to 
weak consumer spending forecasters agreed the economy will remain 
sluggish but stay out of a recession 
robert t parry president and chief executive officer of the 
federal reserve bank of san francisco predicted the gross national 
product after adjustment for inflation will rise only about 2 
percent in 1990 
norman robertson chief economist for mellon bank in pittsburgh 
said american consumers will channel more of their income into 
savings for retailers its going to be a tough year requiring 
an adjustment after the prolonged economic strength during the 
1980s 
one bright spot is that general merchandise inflation has been 
receding according to swanstrom of chicagobased sears the 
nations biggest retailer 
he said sales of general merchandise apparel furniture and 
appliances should grow by about 6 percent this year the same as in 
1989 but inflation will be lower so real sales growth will be 
greater this year he predicted 
convention speakers said retailers who want to thrive in the 
90s when customers will prefer to devote less time to shopping 
must take steps to set themselves apart 
in a timeshort environment consumers will be more attracted 
to stores that have a clear identity said rosalind wells chief 
economist of the retail association 
she said retailers can use a range of characteristics to achieve 
the goal including price service quality convenience fashion 
assortment and inventory depth 
sprawling general merchandise chains that dont tailor their 
strategy to appeal to particular population segments could suffer 
today it is accepted that the general merchandiser is a 
dinosaur said howell of dallasbased penney the 90s will 
confirm that the future belongs to retailers who choose a niche 
and then focus on demographic and lifestyle trends within that 
niche to keep up with the consumer 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900116-0219 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
campeau corps department stores placed under bankruptcy court 
