<TEXT>
bankruptcy court filings released today show 
campeau corps two department store divisions owe billions of 
dollars to a range of unsecured creditors mostly banks and wall 
street firms that helped finance the retailing giants expansion 
the filings in the largest bankruptcy proceeding in retailing 
history showed total assets of 91 billion and liabilities of 77 
billion for the units of the canadian company 
campeau placed them under federal bankruptcy court supervision 
monday so they could reorganize to pay their debts under chapter 11 
of the federal bankruptcy act 
in another development campeaus us subsidiary appointed g 
william miller former federal reserve board chairman and treasury 
secretary as its chairman and chief executive officer 
the company also announced that it would change its name from 
campeau corp us inc to federated stores inc 
the us subsidiary of torontobased campeau operates such 
wellknown department stores as bloomingdales richs and lazarus 
the filing allows the stores to continue operating while the 
company reorganizes 
in papers filed in us bankruptcy court in cincinnati 
federated department stores inc listed assets of 62 billion and 
liabilities of 53 billion allied stores corp listed assets of 
29 billion and liabilities of 24 billion 
federated said its largest unsecured creditor is first boston 
corp which holds 428 million in bonds allied listed campeau 
corp as its largest unsecured creditor with 100 million in bonds 
outstanding 
the filing monday was the largest under chapter 11 by an 
american retailer affecting about 100000 employees and 258 stores 
in the united states and the second largest ever by a 
nonfinancial company after texaco inc which sought court 
protection in april 1987 
miller currently chairman of g william miller amp co inc a 
washingtonbased merchant banking firm has served on the boards of 
campeau federated and allied since 1987 
he originally joined federateds board in 1976 but resigned two 
years later when he became the fed chairman from 1979 to 1981 
miller served as treasury secretary under president carter 
miller was reelected to the federated board in 1981 and after 
campeau bought the retailing company he joined the boards of 
campeau and allied 
campeau also announced other changes regarding senior management 
at its us operations including the resignation of the chairman 
of its retailers ronald w tysoe currently president of both 
campeau corp and campeau us will continue as president of the 
newly renamed federated holding company but he will phase out his 
responsibilities at the canadian parent 
john w burden iii chairman and chief executive officer of 
federated and allied has quit effective jan 31 to pursue other 
interests campeau said the company said it expects to name a 
successor soon to run the retailing operations 
james m zimmerman will remain as president and chief operating 
officer of federated and allied the management teams at all 
department store chains will continue in place 
the management at ralphs grocery co a southern california 
supermarket chain owned by campeau that was not part of the 
bankruptcy court filing will not be changed campeau said 
miller 64 steps into a job created when campeau last week 
split its us operations from the parent company giving them 
operating independence 
the company is now positioned with a strong and experienced 
management team at all levels to manage what has always been a 
highly successful group of american retail businesses with a new 
name that reflects our retailing orientation he said in a news 
release 
tysoe said he has been asked by miller to focus full time on 
restructuring the retailers 
the decision to seek court protection was made late sunday by 
the boards of campeau and the two divisions and reflected campeaus 
inability to pay off 8 billion in debt much of it resulting from 
the 34 billion acquisition of allied in 1986 and the 66 billion 
purchase of federated in 1988 
the decision to seek chapter 11 relief was based on a 
conclusion that action was required at this time in order to 
preserve the operations strength and assets of the two department 
store companies while the corporate debt is restructured campeau 
said in a statement monday 
under chapter 11 the companies get a reprieve from creditors 
and can continue operating while reorganizing their finances but 
all decisions regarding the companies must be approved by a 
bankruptcy judge 
federateds stores include abraham and straus and bloomingdales 
of new york burdines of miami lazarus of cincinnati and richs 
of atlanta allieds stores include the bon marche of seattle 
jordan marsh of boston maas brothers of tampa and sterns of 
paramus nj 
