<DOCNO> AP900116-0236 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
american telephone amp telegraph co has 
traced a computer software failure that blocked millions of 
longdistance calls on monday to a backup system in new york a top 
company official said today 
chairman robert e allen also said atampt plans to offer a 
discount day for businesses who may have lost money because 
customers were unable to do business by telephone 
allen made the comments at a latemorning news conference at the 
companys network operations center in bedminster nj 
the company said mondays outage which blocked longdistance 
calls nationwide for about nine hours was its most widespread 
ever but the martin luther king day holiday prevented the impact 
from being worse 
atampt said it discovered the problem in midafternoon and 
corrected it shortly before midnight well before the start of the 
regular business schedule today 
the company said the system was operating normally today as 
business hours began although atampt did not know exactly what went 
wrong monday 
were seeing traffic starting to build up and the network is 
operating flawlessly spokeswoman daisy ottmann said at 
midmorning 
at the news conference allen said the company did not believe 
the problem was rooted in a computer virus but workers were still 
investigating that possibility 
it does not act like a computer bug allen said 
he said the proposed special discount calling day required 
approval from the federal communications commission 
he said atampt had no liability insurance for regular 
longdistance phone lines but would be covered for any damages 
resulting from loss of business on its tollfree 800 system 
ms ottmann said the company had recently installed new software 
in its system and that the trouble was somewhere within the 
software atampt removed the new software late monday and with it 
the problems that plagued the longdistance network 
the removal of the new software didnt take away any 
processing power of the network ms ottmann said 
about half the longdistance callers on the atampt network got a 
busy signal or a recording saying all circuits were busy the 
company said 
arizona telemarketing inc of phoenix which places 4000 to 
9000 calls a day gave its 40 employees an unexpected holiday in 
the afternoon 
we had to close the place down said miriam benson company 
president 
janice falwin a montclair nj graphics designer who relies 
on her fax machine to present projects to clients in los angeles 
new york and boston said the outage caused her to miss a deadline 
and that could cost her 1000 
deadlines are my life if i miss a deadline i dont eat the 
telephone is like a lifeline to me said falwin who works out of 
her house 
on an average business day 80 million calls go through the atampt 
system said sally sherwood another atampt spokeswoman she said she 
did not know how many calls were attempted monday or how many 
actually went through 
the problem apparently began in one of the companys electronic 
switching centers which transfer calls from one line of the 
longdistance network to another ms ottmann said it then spread 
to the other 100 or so switching centers she said 
its like striking the church bell in a steeple and all the 
other bells resonate this is a vibrating or resonating problem 
she said 
atampt controls about 70 percent of the longdistance market its 
major competitors mci communications corp and us sprint reported 
no problems 
atampt customers are able to use the mci and sprint systems by 
dialing special access codes however atampt operators were 
forbidden even when asked to give out this information for 
competitive reasons ms sherwood said 
ms sherwood said experts from bell laboratories atampts 
research arm assisted in fixing the problem at the companys 
network operations center in bedminster nj the hub of its phone 
system 
certainly intense would an accurate description of the 
activity she said 
a technician at the operations center who spoke on condition of 
anonymity described the scene to the new york times as chaotic 
and almost out of control as engineers worked on the problem 
past problems have been limited to a certain region 
atampt began installing the electronic callswitching gear in 
1987 ms sherwood said 
nothing like this has happened before she said 
the company said the problem affected all its phone lines 
including tollfree 800 numbers and overseas calls except for 
private lines that companies lease between their offices or plants 
some calls were deliberately blocked by atampt to enable it to 
isolate the problem it said 
hotel and airline reservations offices were among hard hit 
businesses 
cindy sheffield phone systems manager for the marriott hotels 
reservation office in omaha neb said the problem was 
devastating because her office wasnt receiving calls from 
customers the office received only 10 percent of its normal call 
volume she said 
american airlines spokeswoman mary oneill in fort worth texas 
said the carrier was experiencing about twothirds fewer calls than 
normal on its reservation lines 
trans midamerica an omahabased marketing company that sells 
temporary motor vehicle licenses couldnt make any long distance 
or 800number calls said florence waymire a company vice 
president 
were dead in the water here today she said 
