<TEXT>
general electric co said tuesday a 
partnership it is organizing will spend about 2 billion during the 
next five years to develop a cleaner more fuelefficient and 
quieter longrange engine for commercial jetliners 
the company says the ge90 designed for longrange widebody 
jets would cost 10 million per unit according to brian h rowe 
senior vice president of ges aircraft engines division based in 
this cincinnati suburb 
the company envisions a potential 50 billion worldwide market 
for the engine 
rowe said the engine could reduce fuel consumption by about 10 
percent he estimated a widebody jetliner using two of the engines 
could save about 400000 gallons of fuel a year 
general electric hopes the ge90 would reduce emissions by 30 
percent from longrange engines now used rowe said 
he also said the engine would be designed to meet more stringent 
federal aviation administration noisereduction standards 
rowe acknowledged that ges major competitors the pratt amp 
whitney division of united technologies corp and britains rolls 
royce are developing rival engines rowe said he hopes ge can 
land at least 30 percent of the global market with the ge90 
the ge90 is to be designed for boeings planned 767x twinengine 
widebody jet being marketed but not yet in commercial service ge 
also is looking for other markets and is talking with jet makers 
mcdonnell douglas and the french producer airbus industrie rowe 
said at a news conference 
our main emphasis at this time is to get the engine launched 
on the 767x rowe said but if somebody else comes along with a 
new application well be very happy 
the french manufacturer snecma a 5050 partner with general 
electric during the past decade in the cfm international joint 
enginemaking venture is expected to be a 25 percent partner in 
the ge90 project rowe said 
the engines would be produced in france and the united states 
parisbased snecma under its current cfm international operation 
with ge produces some cfm engines at a plant in villaroche 
france other cfm engines are made at ges evendale plant 
general electric also hopes mtu a manufacturer based in munich 
will be a partner that is subject to approval by mtus board of 
directors rowe said 
rowe said ge expects that swedish automaker volvo and the 
italian automaker fiat will produce parts for the ge90 both 
companies have produced parts for other ge engines 
other partners may enter the project as well ge officials said 
some of the ge90 parts are likely to be produced at ges plant 
in lynn mass rowe said 
he said the company will spend the next six months lining up its 
partners and getting the research program established developing 
and testing the engine could take five years 
ge hopes to obtain commercial certification of the engine in may 
1994 and enter it in commercial service in 1995 
the engine will provide 75000 to 95000 pounds of thrust ges 
current cf6 engine used in longrange flight develops power of 
52500 to 75000 pounds of thrust ge spokesman dwight weber said 
</TEXT>
