<TEXT>
trans world airlines inc has sold 11 
jumbo jets for 210 million to two leasing companies in an effort 
to raise cash and reduce its large debt company officials said 
tuesday 
its the second time in less than a month that the airline has 
announced the sale of assets on dec 18 twa said it planned to 
sell its chicagolondon route and related assets to american 
airlines for 195 million that deal must be approved by the 
federal government 
the news has angered many employees who believe twa owner carl 
icahn is slowly dismantling the airline which is 27 billion in 
debt and lags behind other major carriers in capital investment 
but industry analysts say selling airplanes and leasing them 
back from the leasing companies is quite common 
most airlines are doing it to raise cash and take advantage of 
high values for aircraft right now said paul turk an analyst 
with avmark inc an aviation consulting firm in arlington va 
but with only 74 of its 213 aircraft owned outright twa has one 
of the lowest ownership percentages in the industry turk said 
twa spokesman don morrison said the airline will use half of the 
210 million from the sale of eight lockheed l1011s and three 
boeing 747s to boost its cash reserves to nearly 1 billion 
the airline will use the other half of the proceeds to trim its 
27 billion in longterm debt morrison said 
twa sold the eight lockheed jets to potomac leasing inc it sold 
the boeing jets to a unit of american express co 
icahn has assured employees in a letter last month that he 
does not intend to dismantle twa 
