<TEXT>
mandatory random testing for drugs and alcohol 
went into effect tuesday for the 90000 men and women who operate 
the nations railroads 
testing began one year after drug abuse was singled out as a 
factor in a 1987 amtrakconrail crash near baltimore that killed 16 
people and injured 175 
the testing program delayed because a lengthy series of court 
battles between the government and railroad unions requires that 
at least 25 percent of railroad engineers brakemen dispatchers 
signalmen conductors and all other railroad employees directly 
involved in the movement of trains be subjected to random testing 
this year 
a full 50 percent of the operations personnel of the nations 
largest railroads must be tested by the end of 1991 for the 
presence of alcohol and such drugs as marijuana cocaine opiates 
amphetamines and phencyclidine also known as pcp 
but claire austin a public affairs officer for the federal 
railroad administration said federal officials expect as many as 
40 percent of those affected by the new requirement to be tested by 
the end of this year alone 
she said railroad administrators expect results will show that 
drugs are a far more serious problem among rail workers than is 
alcohol 
it is very evident to us that drugs are the problem rather 
than alcohol she said pointing to the results of postaccident 
drug and alcohol testing a requirement since 1986 
in that year 738 people were tested with 27 testing positive 
for drugs and seven for alcohol in 1987 770 persons were tested 
with 39 testing positive for drugs and just three testing positive 
for alcohol in 1988 682 people were tested with three testing 
positive for alcohol and 39 testing positive for drugs 
of 21 railroad accidents linked to drugs or alcohol last year 
14 were drugrelated while alcohol was involved in seven of the 
incidents 
the national transportation safety board found in 1988 that 
marijuana use was a factor in the jan 4 1987 accident at chase 
md which left 191 people dead or injured 
the board said drug impairment caused conrail engineer ricky 
gates to speed through several warning systems and into the path of 
an amtrak train 
the presence of marijuana was found in blood and urine samples 
taken from gates he was later convicted of manslaughter and 
sentenced to five years in prison after admitting he smoked 
marijuana and violated several safety procedures 
the board said the effects of the drug caused gates not to 
notice warning signals both inside the engines cab and suspended 
over the tracks until it was too late to make a safe stop 
at the time of the safety boards findings john riley the 
federal railroad administrator said it was clear a random drug 
testing program was needed 
it is not enough to simply talk about the impact marijuana use 
had on this accident riley said at the time if we dont do 
something to prevent it from happening again i mean authorized 
random testing then the lives lost at chase may well have been 
lost in vain 
</TEXT>
