<TEXT>
nations from the east and west nations took the 
first step tuesday toward creating an east european development 
bank that one official said could be working by the end of the year 
delegations from 34 countries including the united states and 
soviet union ended their first meeting by appointing experts to 
work out specific plans for the proposed european bank for 
reconstruction and development in eastern europe said jacques 
attali frances presidential adviser on economic affairs 
we need to be generous but also to help these countries learn 
what they need to learn to transform them into market economies 
said attali who had presided at the twoday meeting 
attali said three groups of experts would begin work and report 
their progress at a second session scheduled for paris on jan 30 
he said a drafting session would be held in paris march 1011 after 
which delegations hopefully would be able to sign an agreement 
the plan reasonably might be ratified and the bank established 
and operating some time this year attali said 
some countries particularly the united states have expressed 
concern about the role of the soviet union in the bank both as 
participant in the capital and eventually even a borrower attali 
said the issue would be addressed during negotiations over the 
draft plan 
disagreements among representatives generally were minor and 
would not stop eventual approval of the bank attali said 
describing the meetings atmosphere as constructive 
french president francois mitterrand proposed creation of the 
bank during a european parliament session oct 25 as a way to help 
east european countries which have removed their hardline 
communist leaders in the past year 
the money will be used for loans for projects in bulgaria 
czechoslovakia east germany hungary poland and romania 
countries already burdened by foreign debts totaling more than 100 
billion 
the idea was endorsed in december at the summit of the 12 
european community countries which proposed a plan for the bank 
delegations on tuesday proposed several amendments to the ec 
plan using the amendments france will draw up a new proposal to 
be presented at the jan 30 session attali said 
attali listed seven issues the working groups would address 
the mission of the bank and whether it should fund only 
private sector projects or include the public sector this is a 
particular concern of the united states 
the conditions under which the new banks money will be lent 
whether at current market rates or in some other way 
criteria for eligibility to borrow from the bank whether 
those criteria will be based on the state of economic reforms in 
any individual east european country 
the amount of capital with which to found the bank attali 
said the current thinking is about 12 billion but no firm figure 
has been reached 
the breakdown of capital participation by each country attali 
said the question had not been studied but no one had rejected the 
idea of the european community holding a majority stake 
the banks method of operation who will run it who will be 
its directors and officers 
where the headquarters will be located attali indicated there 
was no shortage of candidates but refused to reveal them 
the conference participants were all 12 ec members france west 
germany britain italy ireland spain portugal the netherlands 
belgium luxembourg denmark and greece six members of the 
european free trade association austria switzerland finland 
sweden norway and iceland and the united states canada japan 
australia new zealand turkey cyprus malta the soviet union 
yugoslavia bulgaria czechoslovakia east germany hungary poland 
and romania 
