<TEXT>
japan will continue to voluntarily restrict exports 
of passenger autos to the united states to 23 million cars a year 
in the coming year trade minister hikaru matsunaga said wednesday 
the export limit for fiscal 1990 which begins april 1 is the 
same as in the current fiscal year although actual exports are 
expected to total only 2 million autos because of increased 
production in the united states by japanese automakers 
auto exports to the united states in fiscal 1989 are expected 
to be down again from the previous years level matsunaga said 
at a news conference although we consider this trend of decline 
constant for fiscal 1990 we will keep the previous years measures 
in place to confirm the tendency of decline 
the export restraint which dates from 1981 when the us 
government put strong pressure on japan in order to bolster us 
automakers has been considered obsolete for several years because 
japans auto shipments have been under the quota 
but it is still regarded as politically important to keep the 
quota in place while japan and the united states are at loggerheads 
over ways to reduce the 50 billion annual surplus japan runs in 
trade between the two countries 
wednesdays announcement was virtually identical to the one last 
year when the government said the export restraint should be kept 
even though exports to america were declining 
when the export restraints started japanese automakers had a 
big price advantage over us manufacturers but the yens rise 
against the dollar since 1985 has reduced japans price advantage 
japanese car companies have turned increasingly to making autos 
in the united states 
</TEXT>
