<TEXT>
lawyers for a business newsletter said tuesday 
they would fight a court order that halted plans to print a 
frontpage story containing confidential information about the big 
six accounting firm ernst amp young 
the attorneys said the court ruling amounted to unconstitutional 
prior restraint and charged that ernst amp young made no attempt to 
notify newsletter editors that it was seeking the court order 
they received no prior notice james grossberg a washington 
attorney who is part of the team representing the newsletter said 
tuesday that in itself makes this decision blatantly 
unconstitutional 
carl liggio general counsel for ernst amp young told the atlanta 
constitution if we had notified him he would have gone to press 
and defeated the purpose 
arthur w bowman editor of bowmans accounting report said he 
was served with a temporary restraining order at his home the night 
of jan 8 while the january edition of the newsletter was at the 
press stopping him from publishing the article 
the issue was published two days later with a black cover and 
the word censored printed in bold white letters 
the order issued by new york supreme court judge beatrice 
shainswit restrains bowmans accounting report from using 
referring to disseminating or in any way disclosing any 
confidential andor proprietary information of ernst amp young that 
has come into its possession 
ive been in the newsletter business a decade and ive never 
seen anything like this bowman said tuesday 
the article was to have analyzed last junes merger of ernst amp 
whinney and arthur young bowman said his newsletter was the first 
to break the news of that deal when it reported it in the may 17 
1989 issue 
neither the accounting firm nor the newsletter would discuss the 
nature of the information in the article bowman said ernst amp young 
learned of the planned article when he called the firm to check 
some facts 
mort myerson a spokesman for ernst amp young said the issue has 
nothing to do with freedom of the press but centers instead on 
privacy 
this is an issue of proprietary confidential information not 
the first amendment myerson said 
a number of news organizations including the associated press 
the new york times the atlanta journalconstitution the wall 
street journal newsday and the newsletter association of america 
tuesday said they would support the newsletter in its attempt to 
lift the restraining order 
a hearing is scheduled jan 25 in the supreme court of new york 
on bowmans bid to have the order reversed 
